{"title_page": "University of Rajshahi", "text_new": "{{short description|Second Largest University of Bangladesh}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name              = University of Rajshahi\n| native_name       = \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09b6\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc\n| native_name_lang  = bn\n| image             = \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09b6\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b2\u09cb\u0997\u09cb.svg\n| image_size        = 150px\n| image_alt         =\n| caption           =\n| type              = [[Public university|Public]]\n| established       = {{start date|July 6, 1953}}\n| affiliation       = [[University Grants Commission of Bangladesh]]\n| chancellor        = [[President of Bangladesh]]\n| vice_chancellor   = [[M. Abdus Sobhan]]<ref name=\"cd\">{{cite news |title=Prof Sobhan made RU VC again |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/prof-sobhan-made-ru-vc-again-1402015/ |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n| head_label        = Pro Vice-Chancellor\n| head              = Professor Dr. Ananda Kumar Saha\n| provost           = 17 provosts\n| academic_staff    = 1,778 (December 2015)\n| administrative_staff = 2,258 (December 2015)\n| students          = 38,495 (December 2015)<ref>http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/national/2014/04/08/70695</ref>\n| undergrad         = 15,258 (December 2015)\n| postgrad          = 9,125 (December 2015)\n| doctoral          = 2,112 (December 2015)\n| address           = <!-- Please discuss before using -->\n| city              = [[Rajshahi]]\n| country           = Bangladesh\n| postcode          = <!--or, postalcode or zipcode-->\n| coordinates       = {{coord|24.370|88.637|type:edu_region:BD_dim:2000|display=inline,title}}\n| campus            = Urban, {{convert|753|acre|ha|order=flip|abbr=on}}\n| language          = Bengali, English\n| sports            = [[Cricket]], [[association football|football]], [[basketball]], [[karate]]\n| website           = [http://www.ru.ac.bd/ ru.ac.bd]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Rajshahi''', also known as '''Rajshahi University''' or '''RU''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09b6\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc}} ''R\u0101jsh\u0101hi Bish-shobid-daloy'') is a [[public university]] which is the second largest university in [[Bangladesh]], in [[Rajshahi]], a city in northwestern [[Bangladesh]]. It was established in 1953, the second university to be established in what was then [[East Pakistan]]. It ranked as the best research university in Bangladesh in [https://www.scimagoir.com/rankings.php?sector=Higher%20educ.&country=BGD&year=2013&ranking=Research 2019] and third on the Bangladesh University Ranking 2017.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=The ResearchHUB|first1=| title= Bangladesh University Ranking 2017|journal= The ResearchHUB|date=2017|url= http://www.the-research-hub.org/bangladeshi-university-ranking-2017}}</ref> \n\nThe university's 59 departments are organised into ten [[Faculty (division)|faculties]]. Rajshahi University is in a {{convert|753|acre|ha|order=flip|adj=on}} campus in [[Motihar Thana|Motihar]], {{convert|3|km|mi|0}} from the Rajshahi city centre. With 25,000 students and close to 1000 academic staff, it is one of the largest universities in Bangladesh.<ref name=largest>{{cite web | url = http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/APCITY/UNPAN018224.pdf | title = Task Force Review 2003: Education (Bangladesh) | publisher = UN Online Network in Public Administration and Finance\n | year = 2003 | accessdate = 14 March 2006 | pages = 11}}</ref> In addition to hosting programs in engineering, arts, law, sciences, agriculture, [[social science]]s, [[business studies]] and [[medical science]]s, the university houses institutes of higher studies.\n\n== History ==\n\n[[File:Shaheed of Rajshahi University.JPG|thumb|The description on the memorial says, \"Rajshahi University: Those who were martyred during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Liberation war]]\".]]\nThe first proposal to establish a university came in 1917, when [[Calcutta University]] created the [[Sadler Commission]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}} to assess the university system in [[Bengal]]. However, the recommendations of the report had no immediate consequences.\n\n[[University of Dhaka]], established in 1921. Demand for a university in the northern part of East Bengal gained momentum when two universities were set-up quickly in [[West Pakistan]], using funding diverted from East Bengal, without the establishment of any in the east. Students of [[Rajshahi College]] were at the forefront of the movement demanding a new university.<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite book\n | editor = Hasan, A D | year = 2006 | title = University of Rajshahi: A profile | publisher = University of Rajshahi}}</ref> Finally, [[Rajshahi District|Rajshahi]] was selected as the home for the second university in East Bengal and the Rajshahi University Act of 1953 (East Bengal Act XV of 1953) was passed by the East Pakistan provincial Assembly on 31 March 1953.<ref name=\"ugctaka\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/administration/paper.htm\n | title = University of Rajshahi: Glorious 52 years\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n}}</ref> Itrat Hossain Zuberi, the principal of Rajshahi College was appointed its first vice-chancellor.\n\nInitially, the university was housed in temporary locations, such as the local Circuit House and [[Boro Kuthi]], an 18th-century Dutch establishment. B B Hindu Academy, a local school, housed the library, teachers' lounge and the medical centre. The university started out with 20 professors, 161 students (of which 5 were female) and six departments\u2014Bengali, English, History, Law, Philosophy and Economics. In 1964, the offices moved to the permanent campus.\n\nThe 1960s was a turbulent period in Bangladesh, when [[Six point movement|demands for East Pakistani autonomy]] became stronger. The students and staff of the university started playing an increasing role in politics. On 18 February 1969, [[Shamsuzzoha]], a professor, was killed by the police when he tried to prevent them from shooting student demonstrators.<ref name=\"zohapedia\">{{cite book\n|last=Murshed |first=Md Mahbub |year=2012\n|chapter=Shamsuzzoha, Shaheed Mohammad |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Shamsuzzoha,_Shaheed_Mohammad\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A.\n|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref> This date is now commemorated as Zoha Day.<ref name=zohaday>{{cite news\n | url = http://www.thedailystar.net/2007/02/18/d70218070395.htm\n | title = Rajshahi observes Zoha Day today\n | newspaper = The Daily Star\n | date = 18 February 2007\n | accessdate = 14 March 2007\n}}</ref> During the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] of 1971, the campus was used as a base by the [[Pakistan Army]]. A number of professors, students and officers of the university were killed by the Pakistan army during this period.\n\nAfter independence, a new act regarding the administration of the university came into being\u2014the Rajshahi University Act of 1973. The post-independence years saw the university grow steadily in student enrolment and size of the academic staff. However, the 1980s were turbulent for the university, as the students agitated with other institutions of the country against the military rule of [[Hossain Muhammad Ershad]]. Since the early 1990s, the university have seen relative calm and lowering of [[academic term|session]] backlogs, though active student politics remains a contentious issue.\n\n== Emblem ==\nThe circle of the emblem represents the world. An open book is shown in red and gold: red representing one of the colours of the national flag and gold the value of education. The body of the book is blue, the colour of the sky, and at the centre is a ''shapla'' flower ([[Nymphaeaceae]]), the national flower of Bangladesh.\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Main campus===\n[[File:Rajshahi university kendriya shaheed minar 02.jpg|thumb|Shaheed Minar University of Rajshahi]]\n[[File:Kazi Nazrul Islam Auditorium.jpg|thumb|Kazi Nazrul Islam Auditorium University of Rajshahi]]\n[[File:Shabash Bangladesh.jpg|thumb|right|Shabash Bangladesh commemorates the Bangladesh Liberation War]]\n[[Image:ShaheedRU.jpg|thumb|The Shaheed Minar is perhaps the most well-known landmark in the university]]\n[[File:Administration Building of Rajshahi University.jpg|thumb|Front view of the Administration Building of Rajshahi University.]]\nThe university's main campus is in Motihar, on the eastern side of the city of Rajshahi and a mile from the river [[Padma]].<ref name=\"ugctaka\"/> The campus area is nearly {{convert|753|acre|ha|order=flip|abbr=on}}. Access to the walled-off campus is controlled through three security gates. It houses eleven large academic buildings\u2014five for the arts, business studies and [[social science]]s, four for the sciences and two for agricultural studies.\n\nThe central part of the university, accessible by the main gate, is dominated by the administrative building, where the offices of the vice-chancellor and other officials are located. This is flanked by the senate building and the residence of the vice-chancellor on one side (featuring the famous ''[[Shabash Bangladesh]]'' sculpture) and the university mosque and Shaheed Minar complex on the other.<ref name=\"campusplan\">{{cite book\n | editor = Hasan, A D\n | year = 2005\n | title = University of Rajshahi: A profile\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | page = 3\n}}</ref> Behind the administrative building is the central library, around which the four science buildings and three main arts buildings are. The science buildings are named numerically as the \"First Science Building\" and so on. The arts buildings are named after [[Muhammad Shahidullah]], [[Momtazuddin Ahmed]] and [[Rabindranath Tagore]]. More towards the east lie the stadium, the new teacher-student centre and the main auditorium.\n\nThe Kazla gate provides access to the southwestern part of the campus. The Juberi international guest house, [[Rajshahi University School]] and the main residential facilities for the academic staff and university officers are here.<ref name=\"campusplan\"/> Near the residential areas are all five dorms (known as residential halls) for female students. The eastern part of the campus houses the [[Institute of Bangladesh Studies]],<ref name=\"ibsloc\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/ibs/Genesis.htm\n | title = Genesis of IBS\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n}}</ref> the medical and sports facilities, and more residential facilities for the staff\u2014but is dominated by the eleven large dormitories for male students. From the Binodpur gate, the residential halls named after [[Nawab Abdul Latif]], Shamsuzzoha and [[Madarbux]] are to the north, while [[A. K. Fazlul Haq|Sher-e-Bangla]] hall and the oldest dorm Motihar Hall<ref>{{cite news\n | url = http://www.theindependent-bd.com/details.php?nid=80164\n | title = RU budget deficit hurting higher studies\n | newspaper = The Independent\n | location = Dhaka\n | date = 28 April 2005\n | accessdate = 28 April 2008\n}}</ref> lie to the west.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/hall/halls.htm\n | title = Name of Halls of University of Rajshahi\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | accessdate = 28 April 2008\n}}</ref> The second largest [[mass grave]]s in Bangladesh from the 1971 war era is behind Shamsuzzoha Hall.<ref name=\"zhohahall\">{{cite news\n | url = http://www.thedailystar.net/2004/12/11/d41211070571.htm\n | title = Martyrs Memorial inaugurated at RU\n | newspaper = The Daily Star\n | date = 11 December 2004\n | accessdate = 14 October 2006\n}}</ref>\n[[File:Ali Areefur Rehman Seminar Library for the Department of English University of Rajshahi.jpg|thumb|Ali Areefur Rehman Seminar Library for the Department of English University of Rajshahi]]\nThe campus contains many [[mango]] orchards and some litchi trees. The Paris Road is one of the most soothing places inside the campus. It starts from just behind the Juberi international guest house and ends in front of the Shaheed Minar. It has been said that it has been named as Paris Road because of the trees beside this beautiful road originating from Paris.\n\nThe [[Rajshahi]] area is regarded as one of the best mango producing areas in the country,<ref name=\"aam\">{{cite book\n|last=Kabir |first=SM Humayun |year=2012\n|chapter=Mango |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Mango\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A.\n|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref> and these orchards are leased out to professional farmers during the summer, when the fruits grow. The campus also reflects the region's [[Rajshahi silk|silk industry]], fields of [[mulberry]] trees are in the campus for agricultural and research needs. The northern part of the campus houses a [[botanical garden]], which has a good collection of rare plants.\n\n===Other facilities===\n[[Image:Varendra mod.jpg|thumb|Varendra Museum is the oldest in the nation and an important resource for the university]]\nA few miles from the main campus is the [[Varendra Research Museum]],<ref name=varendra>{{cite book\n|last=Chowdhury |first=Saifuddin |year=2012\n|chapter=Varendra Research Museum |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Varendra_Research_Museum\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A.\n|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref> one of the richest repertory of Bengal sculptures in the world.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Rahman | first = Mukhlesur | last2 = | first2 = | title = Sculpture in the Varendra Research Museum : A Descriptive Catalogue| publisher = | location = Rajshahi  | isbn = | publication-date = 1998 |accessdate=24 April 2008 | url = https://www.vedamsbooks.com/no55806.htm | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> Established in 1910 by [[Ramaprasad Chanda]], the museum became a part of the university in the 1960s when a financial crisis threatened its existence. Under the university, the museum has thrived, adding a [[folklore]] gallery to its impressive collection from ancient and medieval Bengal.<ref name=varendra/>\n\nThe Bara Kuthi, where the university was established is still under university control, and is on the Padma not too far from Varendra Museum. The university has an agricultural facility few miles from the main campus. Rajshahi University maintains other facilities across the country including a guesthouse in the capital city, [[Dhaka]].\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nUniversity of Rajshahi is home to many architectural and artistic landmarks, with an area of about almost 304 hectors. The Shaheed Minar is an important example, complete with a [[mural]] designed by Murtaza Bashir. The Senate House is a modern mini-parliament house, has 206 rooms and is fully air-condHitioned. It is usually used for meetings of the senate of the university, but it accommodates national and international conferences, seminars and symposiam.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} In front of the Senate House is [[Shabash Bangladesh]], one of the largest [[Bangladesh Liberation War|war]] memorial sculptures in the nation, designed and constructed by [[Nitun Kundu]].<ref name=\"nitun\">{{cite news\n | url = http://www.thedailystar.net/2006/09/22/d60922110398.htm\n | title = Nitun Kundu\n | newspaper = The Daily Star\n | author = M. Shafiullah\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n | date = 22 September 2006\n}}</ref> The name comes from a poem by [[Sukanta Bhattacharya]] of the same name, the last four lines of which is engraved under the structure.\n\nGolden Jubilee Tower, a 2003 addition to the university's array of sculptures, commemorates its 50th anniversary. It is right beside the main gate. It has also an open theatre and two beautiful murals.  Other well-known buildings include the library and the university mosque.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} The Department of Fine Arts hosts a sizeable collection of contemporary art, while [[Varendra Research Museum|Varendra Museum]] has a large collection of ancient and medieval art.<ref>{{cite news\n | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-51173679.html\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121105044812/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-51173679.html\n | url-status = dead\n | archive-date = 5 November 2012\n | title = US grant for Varendra Museum\n | newspaper = The Independent\n | location = Dhaka\n | author = M. Shafiullah\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n | date = 5 March 2002\n}}</ref>\n\n==Organization and administration==\nThe university is run according to the Rajshahi University Act of 1973.<ref name=\"rubpedia\">{{cite book\n|last=Rahman |first=Mahbubar |year=2012\n|chapter=University of Rajshahi |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=University_of_Rajshahi\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second\n|publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref> The act, passed in 1973, allows the university considerably more autonomy than most other peer institutions. The president of Bangladesh is the de facto [[chancellor (education)|chancellor]], but his role is mainly ceremonial. The highest official after the chancellor is the vice-chancellor, selected by the [[senate]] of the university every four years. The vice-chancellor, as of June 2017, is [[M. Abdus Sobhan]].\n\nOther important officers include the [[Pro-Vice-Chancellor|pro vice-chancellor]], the [[Registrar (education)|registrar]], the controller of examinations and the proctor.<ref name=\"rubpedia\"/> The proctor is in direct charge of student activities and is the official with most direct contact with the students. The most important statutory bodies of the university are the senate, the academic council and the syndicate.<ref name=\"rubpedia\"/>\n\nAs a public institution, most of Rajshahi University's funding comes from the government. The University Grants Commission (UGC) is the body responsible for allocating funds to all [[public universities]].\n\nStudents are admitted after they pass the Higher Secondary Exam (HSC exam). In earlier days students partook in entrance examinations, a separate one for each department. But now students need to partake under unit of different faculty.<ref name=\"admit_1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.varsityadmission.com/Circular/Bachelor/University/Rajshahi_University.php |title=Admission Circular |website=Varsity Admission |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222505/http://www.varsityadmission.com/Circular/Bachelor/University/Rajshahi_University.php |archive-date=27 September 2007 |accessdate=10 October 2006\n}}</ref> This has been a contentious issue,<ref name=\"admit_2\">{{cite web\n| author = The Daily Star\n| publisher = University of Rajshahi | url=http://www.thedailystar.net/magazine/2006/10/02/news.htm\n| title=The State of Higher Education\n| accessdate=10 October 2006\n}}</ref> as there used to be only one exam for each faculty, after which students would be allocated to departments according to their result and choice of program.\n\nThe public University of Rajshahi's tuition fees are relatively low; nevertheless, a hike in admission fees, during the 2006\u201307 session, drew criticism from student bodies.<ref name=\"admit_3\">{{cite news\n| newspaper = The Daily Star | url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2007/03/12/d70312060376.htm| title=RU increases admission and certificate fees| accessdate=10 March 2007 | date = 12 March 2007\n}}</ref> As of 2007, the university awarded a total of 340 scholarships, whose annual value is around 1.1&nbsp;million taka. In addition, there are merit awards given by residential halls, departments and the university itself. Students are eligible for the [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]]'s Gold Medal award.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |author=BSS, Dhaka |author2= |title= Khaleda urges teachers, students: Maintain campus peace |url=http://newsfrombangladesh.net/view.php?hidRecord=59032 |publisher=News from Bangladesh |issn=1563-9304 |date= 31 August 2005|accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nAll colleges of the northern and southern regions of the country used to be affiliated with University of Rajshahi. However, the administration of colleges across the country was taken over by the National University when it was established in 1992.<ref name=\"NUpedia\">{{cite book\n|last1=Hossain |first1=Md Anawar |last2=Khanam |first2=Mobashera |year=2012\n|chapter=National University |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=National_University\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A.\n|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref>\n\n===List of vice-chancellors===\nFollowing is the complete list of the vice-chancellors:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ru.ac.bd/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=68&Itemid=337 | title=Vice-Chancellor's Office | publisher=University of Rajshahi | accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n# [[Itrat Husain Zuberi]] (6 July 1953 \u2013 30 September 1957)\n# [[Momtazuddin Ahmed]] (1 October 1957 \u2013 30 August 1965)\n# [[Muhammad Shamsul Huq]] (31 August 1965 \u2013 4 August 1969)\n# [[Syed Sajjad Hussain]] (5 August 1969 \u2013 18 July 1971)\n# [[Muhammad Abdul Bari (academic)|Muhammad Abdul Bari]] (19 July 1971 \u2013 8 January 1972)\n# [[Khan Sarwar Murshid]] (1 February 1972 \u2013 3 August 1974)\n# [[Mazharul Islam (poet)|Mazharul Islam]] (4 August 1974 \u2013 18 September 1975)\n# [[Syed Ali Ahsan]] (27 September 1975 \u2013 22 June 1977)\n# [[Muhammad Abdul Bari (academic)|Muhammad Abdul Bari]] (7 July 1977 \u2013 17 February 1981)\n# Makbular Rahman Sarkar (26 February 1981 \u2013 22 February 1982)\n# Moslem Huda (22 February 1982 \u2013 20 September 1982)\n# Abdul Rakib (4 October 1982 - 19 March 1988)\n# Amanullah Ahmed (20 March 1988 \u2013 22 July 1992)\n# M. Anisur Rahman (22 July 1992 \u2013 22 August 1994)\n# M. Yusuf Ali (22 August 1994 \u2013 16 February 1997)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-138572|title=Prof Yusuf terms Liberation War 'civil war'|date=2010-05-15|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-06-14|language=en}}</ref>\n# Abdul Khaleque (17 February 1997 \u2013 3 August 1999)\n# [[M. Sayeedur Rahman Khan]] (4 August 1999 \u2013 13 November 2001)\n# Faisul Islam Farouqui (13 November 2001 \u2013 5 June 2005)\n# Md. Altaf Hossain (5 June 2005 \u2013 15 May 2008)\n# Mumnunul Keramat (acting) (16 May 2008 \u2013 28 February 2009)\n# [[M Abdus Sobhan]] (26 February 2009 \u2013 25 February 2013)\n# [[Muhammad Mizanuddin]] (19 March 2013 \u2013 20 March 2017)\n# [[M Abdus Sobhan]] (7 May 2017 \u2013 present)\n\n==Faculties and departments==\n\n{| style='float:right;font-size: 90%;border:1px solid #dddddd; background-color:#fefefe; padding:3px;margin:1em'\n|\n<span style='font-size: 95%'>'''Faculties'''</span>\n* Faculty of Science\n* Faculty of Engineering\n* Faculty of Arts\n* Faculty of Social Science\n* Faculty of Business Studies\n* Faculty of Life & Earth Science\n* Faculty of Law\n* Faculty of Agriculture\n* Faculty of Medicine\n* Faculty of Fine Arts\n\n[[Image:First Science Building, University of Rajshahi.JPG|thumb|left|The Faculty of Engineering: [[Royal Poinciana|Krishnachura]] blossoms in front of the First Science building that houses Physics and Applied Physics & Electronic Engineering]]\n|}\n\nThe university's 58 departments are organised into 10 [[Faculty (division)|faculties]]: Arts, Law, Science, Medicine, Business Studies, Social Sciences, Life and Earth Sciences, Fine Arts and Agriculture.<ref name=\"facultyref\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/faculty.htm\n | title = Faculties of University of Rajshahi\n | website = University of Rajshahi\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090826003410/http://www.ru.ac.bd/faculty.htm\n | archive-date = 26 August 2009\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n}}</ref> The Arts and the Law faculties are the oldest, both established in 1953, closely followed by the Faculty of Science (1956) and the Faculty of Engineering (est. 2009). The university's departments represent the traditional studies in arts, commerce, sciences and engineering through programs such as [[English studies|English]],History, [[Languages]] and [[Linguistics]], Economics, [[Business Studies]], [[Mathematics]], [[Applied Mathematics]] (est.2002), [[Physics]], [[Computer Science & Engineering]], [[Chemistry]], Statistics, Geology & Mining, [[Geography]], [[Psychology]], [[Zoology]], [[Botany]], etc. The university is increasingly emphasising more specialised programs such as [[Pharmacy]], [[Biochemistry]], [[Information engineering (field)|Information]] and [[Communication Engineering]] (ICE) (est. 2000), [[Genetics]] and [[Breeding in the wild|breeding]] (est. 1996).<ref name=\"profile\"/>\n\n===Faculty of Life and Earth Science===\nProminent departments in the faculty of [[Life Sciences|Life]] and [[Earth Sciences]] are\n\n# Geography and Environmental Studies\n# [[Psychology]]\n# [[Botany]]\n# [[Zoology]]\n# Geology & Mining\n# Genetic Engineering & Biotechnology\n# [[Clinical Psychology]]\n\n===Faculty of Arts===\nProminent departments in the faculty of [[Arts]] are\n\n#Department of English\n#Department of Bangla\n#Department of History\n#Department of Islamic History and Culture\n# Islamic Studies\n# Arabic\n# [[Sanskrit]]\n# Urdu\n# Persian Language and Literature\n\n===Faculty of Law===\nThe Faculty of Law has the following departments:\n# Department of Law, University of Rajshahi\n# Department of Law and Land Administration\n\nThe Department of Law is one of the pioneer institutes for graduate level legal education in Bangladesh as well as in South Asia. It was the first institution in South Asia that offered B.Jur. Honours (Bachelor of Jurisprudence). Now it offers LLB (Honours), LLM, Evening LLM, MPhil and PhD in the field of Law. It has a great number of alumni around the world including former president, chief justice, ministers and many of former and current judges of the apex courts of Bangladesh. This is one of the most demandable choice for the High school/college students of Bangladesh.\n\nThe Department of Law and Land Administration was established in the session of 2015-16. It is the pioneer department in Bangladesh as well as in the world in the field of education on Laws relating to land administration, land management and land survey. All core courses of Law are taught here. Graduates of this discipline can apply for all jobs which are for Law graduates, including the positions of Assistant Judge and Judicial Magistrate. They are able to practise as both civil and criminal lawyers and also as Income Tax lawyers. In addition, they are able to apply for jobs in the field of land administration/management. It is currently under a consideration that a separate BCS Cadre (Land) may be created and graduates from this discipline will only be able to apply for those jobs. The programmes offered by this Department include LLB (Honours), LLM, MPhil and PhD.\n \nThese two departments operate through a separate faculty - the Faculty of Law. Initiatives are under process  to establish a new department on the field of Corporate law under this faculty which is going to be the first institution for graduate level education in this field within Bangladesh.\n\nThis faculty is well known for the innovative environment on its premises. A huge library facility is provided here for the students and researchers. This institution provides a great chance to work with some of the greatest legal scholars of this country. The Bangladesh code was developed and was given a great shape for practical use under the leadership of a former chairman of this department in 2006.\n\nStudents of this institution are also popular for their extra-curricular activities. One of the leading debating clubs of the campus belongs to this department. Having a great tradition of mooting, and some nationally popular great legal practitioners as alumni, its Mooting Club RUMCS is well recognised and reputed in Bangladesh.\n\n===Faculty of Engineering===\nThe Faculty of Engineering include the following departments\n# [[Information engineering (field)|Information]] and Communication Engineering (ICE) (est. 2000)\n# Computer Science & Engineering\n# [[Applied Chemistry]] & [[Chemical Engineering]]\n# Materials Science and Engineering\n# Electrical and Electronic Engineering (EEE) (est. 2015)\n\nIn the late 1990 and 2000s, programs in computer science & engineering and Information & Communication Engineering were introduced. The newest addition to the Faculty of Engineering is the Department of Electrical and Electronic Engineering in 2015. The university used to have a separate engineering program through BIT (Bangladesh Institute of Technology) Rajshahi, which has become an independent university: [[Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology]] in 2002. University authorities have decided to merge Applied physics and electronic engineering department with electrical and electronic engineering department on 5 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/58197/ru-to-merge-apee-eee-depts|title=RU to merge APEE, EEE depts|date=2018-12-07 |accessdate=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://somoynews.tv/pages/details/%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%8F%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%AD%E0%A7%82%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%B9%E0%A6%9A%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%9B%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%87-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AD%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%97|title=\u09b0\u09be\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09c7 \u098f\u0995\u09c0\u09ad\u09c2\u09a4 \u09b9\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7 \u09a6\u09c1\u0987 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ad\u09be\u0997\n|date=2018-12-06 |accessdate=2019-06-22}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty of Social Science===\n\nThe Social Science Faculty has the following departments:\n\n# Economics\n# Political Science\n# Social Work\n# Sociology\n# Mass Communication and Journalism\n# Information Science & Library Management\n# Public Administration\n# Anthropology\n# Folklore\n# International Relations<ref name=\"deptinfo\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/?page_id=722\n | title = Departments of University of Rajshahi\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Faculty of Business Studies ===\nFaculty of Business Studies has following departments:\n\n# [[Finance]]\n# Accounting & Information Systems\n# [[Marketing]]\n# [[Management Studies]]\n# Banking & Insurance\n# Tourism & Hospitality Management\n\nAll of these departments are in the Rabindra Building.\n\n===Faculty of Science===\nFaculty of Science has the following departments:\n\n# Mathematics\n# Physics\n# Chemistry\n# Statistics\n# Biochemistry & Molecular Biology\n# Pharmacy\n# [[Department of Population Science and Human Resource Development|Population Science & Human Resource Development]]\n# Applied Mathematics\n# Physical Education and Sports Sciences\n\nMost of these departments are in the 2nd, 3rd and 4th science buildings.\n\n===Faculty of Agriculture===\n\nFaculty of Agriculture has the following departments:\n\n# Agronomy and Agricultural Extension\n# Crop Science and Technology was established in 2005. It offers a 4-year [[Bachelor of Science in Agriculture|B.Sc.Ag.(Hons)]] degree and 18 months [[Master of Science|M.S.]] degree. [[M.Phil]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (Ph.D) degrees are also offered. About 250 students are studying in the department.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dept.ru.ac.bd/cst/?p=258 |title=Dept. of Crop Science and Technology |website=Crop Science & Technology}}</ref>\n# Fisheries\n# Veterinary & Animal Science\nAll of these department are in the Agricultural Faculty Building.  Only 'practical work' is performing in Narikelbaria Campus. Founded in 2000, the Faculty of [[Agricultural Science|Agriculture]] was formed when a local agricultural college was absorbed into the university.\n\n===Faculty of Medicine===\nThis faculty is organised differently from other disciplines. Medical education is provided by seven medical colleges located around Rajshahi Division and Khulna Division. Though these colleges are autonomous to a large extent, the degrees are conferred by Rajshahi University. [[Rajshahi Medical College]] is the oldest medical college under administration of the university and is a few miles west of the university campus along with the highly equipped 1000-bed [[Rajshahi Medical College Hospital]].\n\nGovernment medical colleges under the supervision of Rajshahi University:\n\n# [[Rajshahi Medical College]]\n# [[Pabna Medical College]]\n# [[Shaheed Ziaur Rahman Medical College]]\n# [[Rangpur Medical College]]\n# [[Dinajpur Medical College]]\n# [[Kushtia Medical College]]\n# [[Jessore Medical College]]\n# [[Khulna Medical College]]\n# [[Satkhira Medical College]]\n# Shaheed M. Munsur Ali Medical College, Sirajgonj\n# Institute of medical Technology, Rajshahi (BSPT)\n\n===Institutes===\nThere are six institutes of Rajshahi University.\n\n# Institutes of Bangladesh Studies\n# Institutes of Biological Science\n# Institute of Business Administration\n# Institute of Education and Research\n# Institute of Environmental Science\n# Institute of English and Other Languages\n\n==Affiliating colleges under Rajshahi University==\n# BCMC college of ENGINEERING and TECHNOLOGY, Jessore\n# Rangpur Engineering College\n# International Institute of Applied Science & Technology, Rangpur\n# Tomaltola Agricultural College, Nator\n# South East Engineering College, Khulna\n# Epsilon Engineering College, Rajshahi\n# Rajshahi College of Science & Technology, Rajshahi\n# Khwaja Yunus Ali Medical College, Rajshahi\n# Islami Bank Medical College, Rajshahi\n# Barind Medical College, Rajshahi\n# TMSS Medical College, Bogra\n# Prime Medical College, Rangpur\n# Udoyon Dental College, Rajshahi\n# Institute of Health Technology, Rajshahi\n# Northern Medical College, Rangpur\n# Rangpur Dental College\n# Bangladesh Police Academy, Sardah, Rajshahi\n# Imperial College of Engineering, Khulna\n#South-East Engineering College, Khulna\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Housing===\n\nThe university has 18 residential halls for students, six for women and eleven for men and one International Dormitory. The halls are named after prominent Bangladeshi historical and cultural figures, some of them from Rajshahi. The largest men's hall is Shahid Habibur Rahman Hall, named after a mathematics professor killed on campus during the 1971 war by the Pakistani Army. The largest women's hall is Monnujan Hall, followed by Begum Rokeya Hall, named after [[Rokeya Sakhawat Hussain]], a leading figure in women's rights activism in Bengal.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\nThe housing system can accommodate  more than 10,000 students, which has created a deepening accommodation crisis as the student body has risen to 25,000.<ref name=\"BDToday\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ru.ac.bd/administration/paper.htm|title=University of Rajshahi |accessdate=29 April 2008 |author=  |date=5 August 2005 |year= |work=Glorious 52 years |publisher=The Bangladesh Today   |pages= }}</ref> Apart from the seat limitations, the amenities of these halls do not always meet decent accommodation standards.<ref name=\"amen_1\">{{cite news\n| author = S.M. Humayun Kabir\n| newspaper = New Age\n| url=http://www.newagebd.com/2005/jun/09/met.html\n| title=Students live with poor amenities at University of Rajshahi | accessdate=10 October 2006 | date = 5 June 2005\n}}</ref> This has led to the establishment of many privately owned off-campus \"[[mess]]es\". The residential halls provide meals, which are subsidised by the university authorities.\n\n====Names of halls====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!No\n! Name\n!Name of Provosts\n!PABX Telephone\n|-\n|01\n|Sher-e-Bangla Fazlul Haque Hall\n|Mostofa Tarequl Ahsan\n|4191\n|-\n|02\n|Shah Makhdum Hall\n|M. Zahangir Alam\n|4193\n|-\n|03\n|Nawab Abdul Latif Hall\n| Bipul Kumar Biswas\n|4195\n|-\n|04\n|Syed Amir Ali Hall\n|Golam Mortuza\n|4194\n|-\n|05\n|Shahid Shamsuzzoha Hall\n|Dr.M.Julkar naeen\n\n|-\n|06\n|Shahid Habibur Rahman Hall\n|Prof. Abdur Rahman\n|4200\n|-\n|07\n|Motihar Hall\n|Afrouzzaman Khan Chowdhury\n|4192\n|-\n|08\n|Madar Baksh Hall\n|M. Abdur Rahim Khan\n|4198\n|-\n|09\n|Shahid Sohrawardi Hall\n|M.Robiul \n|4197\n|-\n|10\n|Shahid Ziaur Rahman Hall\n|A.N.M. Zahangir Kabir\n|4199\n|-\n|11\n|Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Hall\n|Mohd. Nurul Islam\n|4190\n|-\n|12\n|Monnujan Hall\n|Irin Banu Luci\n|4204\n|-\n|13\n|Begum Rokeya Hall\n|Nazma Afroz\n|4202\n|-\n|14\n|Tapashi Rabeya Hall\n|Hosne Ara Jesmin\n|4201\n|-\n|15\n|Begum Khaleda Zia Hall\n|Salma Banu\n|4203\n|-\n|16\n|Rahamatunnesa Hall\n|Mele Jesmin\n|4205\n|-\n|17\n|Bongomata Sheikh Fazilatun-nesa Hall\n|Fahima Khatun\n|711206\n|-\n|18\n|Shaheed Mir Abdul Qauyum Int\u2019l Dormitory\n|\n|711237\n|}\n\n===Activities===\n\nThe physical education department of the university has 27 instructors and is equipped with a 25,000-seat stadium, two gymnasiums, one swimming pool, four [[association football|football]] grounds, one hockey ground, four tennis courts, two basketball courts and a squash court.\n\nThe Teacher Students Center was designed to be the centre of cultural activities of the university. Reception of fresh students, celebration of national holidays, and the annual cultural competition are key cultural events at the campus.<ref name=\"rubpedia\" /> The university is home to recitation groups like ''Shwanan'', and drama groups like ''Anushilon'' and Rajshahi University Drama Association (RUDA).<ref name=\"drama_1\">{{cite news\n| newspaper = New Age\n| url=http://www.newagebd.com/2006/jul/07/met.html\n| title=53rd founding anniversary of RU observed\n| accessdate=17 March 2007\n| date = 7 July 2006\n}}</ref> A vibrant fine arts scene thrives around the Department of Fine Arts, and the campus hosts exhibitions each year. The university has branches of all major national cultural groups, including Udichi and ''Gono Natto Shongstha''.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\nDuring the three major national days \u2014 [[Language Movement Day]] (21 February), [[Bangladeshi Independence Day|Independence Day]] (26 March) and [[Victory Day (Bangladesh)|Victory Day]] (16 December) \u2014  the university hosts public meetings, cultural programs and political activities. On these days, students and teachers, going barefoot, congregate around the Shaheed Minar and pay their respect. During the major Muslim religious occasions of [[Muslim holidays|Eid]], the university is usually deserted as students go home to be with their families. Other religiously important days like [[Mid-Sha'ban|Shabe-barat]] are observed through discussions and religious activities. The major Hindu festival celebrated in the university is [[Saraswati Puja]]\u2014[[Saraswati]], the [[goddess]] of knowledge, is worshiped in a central location as well as individually in many residential halls.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} The Bengali new year, ''[[Pohela Baisakh]]'' is also observed with much pomp.<ref name=\"nobobarsho_1\">{{cite news\n| newspaper =New Age| url=http://www.newagebd.com/2006/apr/16/met.html| title=Grand celebrations in Rajshahi | accessdate=10 October 2006\n| date = 16 April 2006\n}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* Physicist [[Arun Kumar Basak]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dept.ru.ac.bd/physics/faculty/current-faculty-members/|title=Current Faculty Members |work=Rajshahi University |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Former Minister Mr Narayan Chandra Chanda MP\n* Former State Minister for Home affairs-[[Shamsul Hoque Tuku]] MP\n* Singer [[Farida Parveen]]\n* Singer [[Andrew Kishor]]\n* Cricketer [[Al-Amin Hossain]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Isam |first=Mohammad |date=14 August 2014 |title=Hard work nothing new to Al-Amin |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/769977.html |work=ESPNcricinfo |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Writer [[Selina Hossain]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barguna.gov.bd/node/497952-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%96%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AC- |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519023347/http://www.barguna.gov.bd/node/497952-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%96%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AC- |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 May 2015 |script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09bf\u0996\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a4 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac |trans-title=Famous personalities |website=Bangladesh National Portal |language=bn |access-date=24 March 2017 }}</ref>\n* Writer [[Hasan Azizul Huq]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Mahfuj |first=Emran |date=5 July 2015 |title='Bangalis are trying to get ahead by forgetting the past' |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/op-ed/bangalis-are-trying-get-ahead-forgetting-the-past-107530 |newspaper=The Daily Star |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Physicist [[M. Sayeedur Rahman Khan]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ru.ac.bd/vc/?page_id=44 |title=List of former Vice Chancellor |website=University of Rajshahi |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Poet [[Mahadev Saha]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mahadevsaha.com/ |title=Mahadev Saha |website=Mahadev Saha |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Director [[Giasuddin Selim]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-203688 |title=Giasuddin Selim: How to bring about a revolution in Bangladeshi filmdom |newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n* Playwright [[Malay Bhowmick]]\n\n==Incidents and controversies==\nDuring the 1980s, the four-year honours course took as long as eight years due to the session backlogs, resulting mainly from conflicts between factions of political groups. Since the early 1990s, [[student politics]] has been comparatively calmer, with student body elections not being held for more than a decade. The student groups have been demanding elections whereas others feel student politics should be banned.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn late 2004 and early 2005, two professors of Rajshahi University got assassinated within three months: Professor Yunus from the Economics department in December 2004<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |author= |author2= |title= 90 RU teachers want VC to quit over Taher killing |url=http://www.newagebd.com/2006/mar/04/nat.html |newspaper=New Age|id= |date= 4 March 2006|accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> and Professor Taher from the Geology and Mining department in February 2005.<ref name=\"Taher\">{{cite news |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/print_news.php?nid=37686 |title=Verdict in RU Prof Taher murder case today |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=22 May 2008 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> Both murders were suspected to be driven by political motivations. In 2006, the commander of [[Jamaat-ul-Mujahideen Bangladesh|Jama'atul Mujahideen Bangladesh]] admitted to the [[Rapid Action Battalion|RAB]] interrogators that his operatives carried out the attack on Yunus, as well as the 2004 attack on writer [[Humayun Azad]], the murder of another writer, bomb blasts, and attacks on cinemas.<ref>{{cite news |date=5 June 2006 |title=JMB also killed writer of Tangail |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2006/06/05/d6060501128.htm |newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\nAround the same time, a controversy over the hiring of over 500 new employees broke; detractors suggested that they were hired illegally, either in return for money or for political reasons.<ref name=\"corruption_1\">{{cite news | title=Recruitment in RU postponed amid employees' agitation | url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2006/10/08/d6100801127.htm | newspaper = Daily Star | date = 8 October 2006 | accessdate=10 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nSince the new millennium, much attention has been focused on politics among university teaching staff. Observers have claimed that the teaching staff have been thoroughly polarised according to party lines in national politics.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\nIn 2005, [[Muhammad Asadullah Al-Ghalib]] of the university was arrested for links with the [[Ahle Hadith Andolon Bangladesh]], but was acquitted in 2008.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn August 2007, six detained professors of the university were temporarily suspended for their involvement in organising protests for restoring that violated Emergency Power Rules,<ref>{{cite news | title=RU suspends its 6 detained teachers\n| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/story.php?nid=2997 | newspaper = Daily Star | date = 24 February 2005 | accessdate=10 March 2007\n}}</ref> though they were discharged later from allegations and returned to the university with proper honour.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn November 2017, a woman student was abducted from the university campus, sparking protests by students demanding her rescue and improved security on the campus.<ref name=\"protesting_2018_11_18_daily_sun_com\">[http://www.daily-sun.com/post/269497/Rajshahi-University-students-besiege-VC%E2%80%99s-residence-protesting-student-abduction \"Rajshahi University students besiege VC\u2019s residence protesting student abduction,\"] November 18, 2017, ''Daily Sun'' ('''daily-sun.com'''), Bangladesh</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, protests and counter-violence erupted at various universities, particularly RU, over the \"[[Bangladesh Quota Reform Protests 2018|quota reform movement]],\" which sought to change the quota system that allocated 56% of Bangladesh government jobs to specific \"entitled\" classes. RU's vice-chancellor, Professor M. Abdus Sobhan, dismissed the quota-reform movement as an \"anti-government movement with a motive to carry out sabotage.\"<ref name=\"rajshahi_police_2018_07_09_thedailystar_net\">[https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/rajshahi-police-saw-nothing-1602220 \"Rajshahi police saw nothing!\"], July 9, 2018 ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]]'', Bangladesh</ref>\n\nRU student and quota-reform movement leader Toriqul Islam, and 15 others, were attacked during their protest march, July 2, 2018, by opposing students. A prominent Bangladesh newspaper, the ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]],'' which filmed the incident, identified 10 of the attackers as leaders and activists of the [[Bangladesh Chhatra League]] (BCL), a pro-[[Awami League]] (Bangladesh's ruling party) student organisation.  Video footage and photos published in Bangladeshi media showed BCL men\u2014with sticks, bamboo poles, a dagger and a hammer\u2014beating Toriqul, who suffered a broken leg and severe head injury. Several police officers standing nearby (unaware the incident was being filmed) did not intervene until the attack was finished, then took the victim to hospital\u2014but without arresting any of the attackers, publicly denying it was anything more than a \"scuffle.\" University authorities declined to investigate, for lack of a filed complaint. Images of the attack, distributed on social media, sparked widespread criticism over police and university administration inaction.<ref name=\"rajshahi_police_2018_07_09_thedailystar_net\" /><ref name=\"injured_quota_protester_2018_07_08_dhaka_tribune\">[https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2018/07/08/injured-quota-reform-activist-tariqul-being-moved-to-dhaka-for-treatment \"Injured quota protester Tariqul moved to Dhaka,\"] July 8, 2018, ''[[Dhaka Tribune]]''</ref><ref name=\"quota_reform_activist_2018_07_06_prothomalo_com\">[http://en.prothomalo.com/bangladesh/news/179205/Quota-reform-activist-Toriqul-denied-treatment-in \"Quota reform activist Toriqul denied treatment in govt hospital,\"] July 6, 2018, ''[[Daily Prothom Alo]]''</ref><ref name=\"injured_ru_quota_reformist_2018_07_08_prothomalo_com\">[http://en.prothomalo.com/bangladesh/news/179318/Injured-RU-quota-reformist-Tariqul-being-brought \"Injured RU quota reformist Toriqul being brought to Dhaka,\"] July 8, 2018, ''[[Daily Prothom Alo]]''</ref>\n\nDespite student Toriqul's unresolved major injuries, the university's [[Rajshahi Medical College]] Hospital discharged him July 5, 2018, forcing his doctor to arrange for immediate surgery elsewhere.<ref name=\"quota_reform_activist_2018_07_06_prothomalo_com\" /><ref name=\"injured_ru_quota_reformist_2018_07_08_prothomalo_com\" /><ref name=\"injured_toriqul_2018_07_09_thedailystar_net\">[https://www.thedailystar.net/country/injured-quota-reform-leader-toriqul-islam-being-brought-to-dhaka-from-rajshahi-better-treatment-1601917 \"Injured quota reform leader Toriqul Islam being brought to Dhaka,\"] July 8, 2018 ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]]'', Bangladesh</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"120px\">\nParis road rajshahi.JPG|Paris Road\nMedical Center, University of Rajshahi (1).jpg|Medical Center\nRailline, inside of rajshahi university.jpg|Rail Line\nRajshahi University Shaheed Minar, Rajshahi.jpg|Shaheed Minar\nRajshahi University Stadium.jpg|Stadium\nSwiming phool, rajshahi university.jpg|Swimming Pool\nMain gate of university of rajshahi.jpg|Main Gate\nTSCC, University of Rajshahi (1).jpg|TSCC\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Bangladesh}}\n{{Commons category|University of Rajshahi}}\n* [[List of universities in Bangladesh]]\n* [[Islamic University of Technology]] (IUT)\n* [[Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology]] (BUET)\n* [[University of Dhaka]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation\n | author = University of Rajshahi\n | year = 2006\n | title = University of Rajshahi: A Profile\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | postscript = <!--None-->\n}}.\n* {{Cite web\n | author = University Grant Commission\n | year = 2004\n | title = University of Rajshahi\n | url = http://www.ugc.org/rajsahai_uni.htm\n | postscript = <!--None-->\n}}.\n* {{Cite web\n | author = University of Rajshahi\n | year = 2004\n | title = University of Rajshahi: Glorious 52 years\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/administration/paper.htm\n | postscript = <!--None-->\n}}.\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ru.ac.bd Official website]\n* {{Facebook|UniversityofRU}}\n{{University of Rajshahi}}\n{{Public Universities of Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1953]]\n[[Category:Public universities of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:University of Rajshahi| ]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Rajshahi]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Second Largest University of Bangladesh}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name              = University of Rajshahi\n| native_name       = \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09b6\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc\n| native_name_lang  = bn\n| image             = \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09b6\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b2\u09cb\u0997\u09cb.svg\n| image_size        = 150px\n| image_alt         =\n| caption           =\n| type              = [[Public university|Public]]\n| established       = {{start date|July 6, 1953}}\n| affiliation       = [[University Grants Commission of Bangladesh]]\n| chancellor        = [[President of Bangladesh]]\n| vice_chancellor   = [[M. Abdus Sobhan]]<ref name=\"cd\">{{cite news |title=Prof Sobhan made RU VC again |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/country/prof-sobhan-made-ru-vc-again-1402015/ |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n| head_label        = Pro Vice-Chancellor\n| head              = Professor Dr. Ananda Kumar Saha\n| provost           = 17 provosts\n| academic_staff    = 1,778 (December 2015)\n| administrative_staff = 2,258 (December 2015)\n| students          = 38,495 (December 2015)<ref>http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/national/2014/04/08/70695</ref>\n| undergrad         = 15,258 (December 2015)\n| postgrad          = 9,125 (December 2015)\n| doctoral          = 2,112 (December 2015)\n| address           = <!-- Please discuss before using -->\n| city              = [[Rajshahi]]\n| country           = Bangladesh\n| postcode          = <!--or, postalcode or zipcode-->\n| coordinates       = {{coord|24.370|88.637|type:edu_region:BD_dim:2000|display=inline,title}}\n| campus            = Urban, {{convert|753|acre|ha|order=flip|abbr=on}}\n| language          = Bengali, English\n| sports            = [[Cricket]], [[association football|football]], [[basketball]], [[karate]]\n| website           = [http://www.ru.ac.bd/ ru.ac.bd]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Rajshahi''', also known as '''Rajshahi University''' or '''RU''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09b6\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc}} ''R\u0101jsh\u0101hi Bish-shobid-daloy'') is a [[public university]] which is the second largest university in [[Bangladesh]], in [[Rajshahi]], a city in northwestern [[Bangladesh]]. It was established in 1953, the second university to be established in what was then [[East Pakistan]]. The university is ranked third on the Bangladesh University Ranking 2017.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=The ResearchHUB|first1=| title= Bangladesh University Ranking 2017|journal= The ResearchHUB|date=2017|url= http://www.the-research-hub.org/bangladeshi-university-ranking-2017}}</ref>\n\nThe university's 59 departments are organised into ten [[Faculty (division)|faculties]]. Rajshahi University is in a {{convert|753|acre|ha|order=flip|adj=on}} campus in [[Motihar Thana|Motihar]], {{convert|3|km|mi|0}} from the Rajshahi city centre. With 25,000 students and close to 1000 academic staff, it is one of the largest universities in Bangladesh.<ref name=largest>{{cite web | url = http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/APCITY/UNPAN018224.pdf | title = Task Force Review 2003: Education (Bangladesh) | publisher = UN Online Network in Public Administration and Finance\n | year = 2003 | accessdate = 14 March 2006 | pages = 11}}</ref> In addition to hosting programs in engineering, arts, law, sciences, agriculture, [[social science]]s, [[business studies]] and [[medical science]]s, the university houses institutes of higher studies.\n\n== History ==\n\n[[File:Shaheed of Rajshahi University.JPG|thumb|The description on the memorial says, \"Rajshahi University: Those who were martyred during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Liberation war]]\".]]\nThe first proposal to establish a university came in 1917, when [[Calcutta University]] created the [[Sadler Commission]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}} to assess the university system in [[Bengal]]. However, the recommendations of the report had no immediate consequences.\n\n[[University of Dhaka]], established in 1921. Demand for a university in the northern part of East Bengal gained momentum when two universities were set-up quickly in [[West Pakistan]], using funding diverted from East Bengal, without the establishment of any in the east. Students of [[Rajshahi College]] were at the forefront of the movement demanding a new university.<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite book\n | editor = Hasan, A D | year = 2006 | title = University of Rajshahi: A profile | publisher = University of Rajshahi}}</ref> Finally, [[Rajshahi District|Rajshahi]] was selected as the home for the second university in East Bengal and the Rajshahi University Act of 1953 (East Bengal Act XV of 1953) was passed by the East Pakistan provincial Assembly on 31 March 1953.<ref name=\"ugctaka\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/administration/paper.htm\n | title = University of Rajshahi: Glorious 52 years\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n}}</ref> Itrat Hossain Zuberi, the principal of Rajshahi College was appointed its first vice-chancellor.\n\nInitially, the university was housed in temporary locations, such as the local Circuit House and [[Boro Kuthi]], an 18th-century Dutch establishment. B B Hindu Academy, a local school, housed the library, teachers' lounge and the medical centre. The university started out with 20 professors, 161 students (of which 5 were female) and six departments\u2014Bengali, English, History, Law, Philosophy and Economics. In 1964, the offices moved to the permanent campus.\n\nThe 1960s was a turbulent period in Bangladesh, when [[Six point movement|demands for East Pakistani autonomy]] became stronger. The students and staff of the university started playing an increasing role in politics. On 18 February 1969, [[Shamsuzzoha]], a professor, was killed by the police when he tried to prevent them from shooting student demonstrators.<ref name=\"zohapedia\">{{cite book\n|last=Murshed |first=Md Mahbub |year=2012\n|chapter=Shamsuzzoha, Shaheed Mohammad |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Shamsuzzoha,_Shaheed_Mohammad\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A.\n|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref> This date is now commemorated as Zoha Day.<ref name=zohaday>{{cite news\n | url = http://www.thedailystar.net/2007/02/18/d70218070395.htm\n | title = Rajshahi observes Zoha Day today\n | newspaper = The Daily Star\n | date = 18 February 2007\n | accessdate = 14 March 2007\n}}</ref> During the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] of 1971, the campus was used as a base by the [[Pakistan Army]]. A number of professors, students and officers of the university were killed by the Pakistan army during this period.\n\nAfter independence, a new act regarding the administration of the university came into being\u2014the Rajshahi University Act of 1973. The post-independence years saw the university grow steadily in student enrolment and size of the academic staff. However, the 1980s were turbulent for the university, as the students agitated with other institutions of the country against the military rule of [[Hossain Muhammad Ershad]]. Since the early 1990s, the university have seen relative calm and lowering of [[academic term|session]] backlogs, though active student politics remains a contentious issue.\n\n== Emblem ==\nThe circle of the emblem represents the world. An open book is shown in red and gold: red representing one of the colours of the national flag and gold the value of education. The body of the book is blue, the colour of the sky, and at the centre is a ''shapla'' flower ([[Nymphaeaceae]]), the national flower of Bangladesh.\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Main campus===\n[[File:Rajshahi university kendriya shaheed minar 02.jpg|thumb|Shaheed Minar University of Rajshahi]]\n[[File:Kazi Nazrul Islam Auditorium.jpg|thumb|Kazi Nazrul Islam Auditorium University of Rajshahi]]\n[[File:Shabash Bangladesh.jpg|thumb|right|Shabash Bangladesh commemorates the Bangladesh Liberation War]]\n[[Image:ShaheedRU.jpg|thumb|The Shaheed Minar is perhaps the most well-known landmark in the university]]\n[[File:Administration Building of Rajshahi University.jpg|thumb|Front view of the Administration Building of Rajshahi University.]]\nThe university's main campus is in Motihar, on the eastern side of the city of Rajshahi and a mile from the river [[Padma]].<ref name=\"ugctaka\"/> The campus area is nearly {{convert|753|acre|ha|order=flip|abbr=on}}. Access to the walled-off campus is controlled through three security gates. It houses eleven large academic buildings\u2014five for the arts, business studies and [[social science]]s, four for the sciences and two for agricultural studies.\n\nThe central part of the university, accessible by the main gate, is dominated by the administrative building, where the offices of the vice-chancellor and other officials are located. This is flanked by the senate building and the residence of the vice-chancellor on one side (featuring the famous ''[[Shabash Bangladesh]]'' sculpture) and the university mosque and Shaheed Minar complex on the other.<ref name=\"campusplan\">{{cite book\n | editor = Hasan, A D\n | year = 2005\n | title = University of Rajshahi: A profile\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | page = 3\n}}</ref> Behind the administrative building is the central library, around which the four science buildings and three main arts buildings are. The science buildings are named numerically as the \"First Science Building\" and so on. The arts buildings are named after [[Muhammad Shahidullah]], [[Momtazuddin Ahmed]] and [[Rabindranath Tagore]]. More towards the east lie the stadium, the new teacher-student centre and the main auditorium.\n\nThe Kazla gate provides access to the southwestern part of the campus. The Juberi international guest house, [[Rajshahi University School]] and the main residential facilities for the academic staff and university officers are here.<ref name=\"campusplan\"/> Near the residential areas are all five dorms (known as residential halls) for female students. The eastern part of the campus houses the [[Institute of Bangladesh Studies]],<ref name=\"ibsloc\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/ibs/Genesis.htm\n | title = Genesis of IBS\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n}}</ref> the medical and sports facilities, and more residential facilities for the staff\u2014but is dominated by the eleven large dormitories for male students. From the Binodpur gate, the residential halls named after [[Nawab Abdul Latif]], Shamsuzzoha and [[Madarbux]] are to the north, while [[A. K. Fazlul Haq|Sher-e-Bangla]] hall and the oldest dorm Motihar Hall<ref>{{cite news\n | url = http://www.theindependent-bd.com/details.php?nid=80164\n | title = RU budget deficit hurting higher studies\n | newspaper = The Independent\n | location = Dhaka\n | date = 28 April 2005\n | accessdate = 28 April 2008\n}}</ref> lie to the west.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/hall/halls.htm\n | title = Name of Halls of University of Rajshahi\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | accessdate = 28 April 2008\n}}</ref> The second largest [[mass grave]]s in Bangladesh from the 1971 war era is behind Shamsuzzoha Hall.<ref name=\"zhohahall\">{{cite news\n | url = http://www.thedailystar.net/2004/12/11/d41211070571.htm\n | title = Martyrs Memorial inaugurated at RU\n | newspaper = The Daily Star\n | date = 11 December 2004\n | accessdate = 14 October 2006\n}}</ref>\n[[File:Ali Areefur Rehman Seminar Library for the Department of English University of Rajshahi.jpg|thumb|Ali Areefur Rehman Seminar Library for the Department of English University of Rajshahi]]\nThe campus contains many [[mango]] orchards and some litchi trees. The Paris Road is one of the most soothing places inside the campus. It starts from just behind the Juberi international guest house and ends in front of the Shaheed Minar. It has been said that it has been named as Paris Road because of the trees beside this beautiful road originating from Paris.\n\nThe [[Rajshahi]] area is regarded as one of the best mango producing areas in the country,<ref name=\"aam\">{{cite book\n|last=Kabir |first=SM Humayun |year=2012\n|chapter=Mango |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Mango\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A.\n|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref> and these orchards are leased out to professional farmers during the summer, when the fruits grow. The campus also reflects the region's [[Rajshahi silk|silk industry]], fields of [[mulberry]] trees are in the campus for agricultural and research needs. The northern part of the campus houses a [[botanical garden]], which has a good collection of rare plants.\n\n===Other facilities===\n[[Image:Varendra mod.jpg|thumb|Varendra Museum is the oldest in the nation and an important resource for the university]]\nA few miles from the main campus is the [[Varendra Research Museum]],<ref name=varendra>{{cite book\n|last=Chowdhury |first=Saifuddin |year=2012\n|chapter=Varendra Research Museum |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Varendra_Research_Museum\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A.\n|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref> one of the richest repertory of Bengal sculptures in the world.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Rahman | first = Mukhlesur | last2 = | first2 = | title = Sculpture in the Varendra Research Museum : A Descriptive Catalogue| publisher = | location = Rajshahi  | isbn = | publication-date = 1998 |accessdate=24 April 2008 | url = https://www.vedamsbooks.com/no55806.htm | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> Established in 1910 by [[Ramaprasad Chanda]], the museum became a part of the university in the 1960s when a financial crisis threatened its existence. Under the university, the museum has thrived, adding a [[folklore]] gallery to its impressive collection from ancient and medieval Bengal.<ref name=varendra/>\n\nThe Bara Kuthi, where the university was established is still under university control, and is on the Padma not too far from Varendra Museum. The university has an agricultural facility few miles from the main campus. Rajshahi University maintains other facilities across the country including a guesthouse in the capital city, [[Dhaka]].\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nUniversity of Rajshahi is home to many architectural and artistic landmarks, with an area of about almost 304 hectors. The Shaheed Minar is an important example, complete with a [[mural]] designed by Murtaza Bashir. The Senate House is a modern mini-parliament house, has 206 rooms and is fully air-condHitioned. It is usually used for meetings of the senate of the university, but it accommodates national and international conferences, seminars and symposiam.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} In front of the Senate House is [[Shabash Bangladesh]], one of the largest [[Bangladesh Liberation War|war]] memorial sculptures in the nation, designed and constructed by [[Nitun Kundu]].<ref name=\"nitun\">{{cite news\n | url = http://www.thedailystar.net/2006/09/22/d60922110398.htm\n | title = Nitun Kundu\n | newspaper = The Daily Star\n | author = M. Shafiullah\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n | date = 22 September 2006\n}}</ref> The name comes from a poem by [[Sukanta Bhattacharya]] of the same name, the last four lines of which is engraved under the structure.\n\nGolden Jubilee Tower, a 2003 addition to the university's array of sculptures, commemorates its 50th anniversary. It is right beside the main gate. It has also an open theatre and two beautiful murals.  Other well-known buildings include the library and the university mosque.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} The Department of Fine Arts hosts a sizeable collection of contemporary art, while [[Varendra Research Museum|Varendra Museum]] has a large collection of ancient and medieval art.<ref>{{cite news\n | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-51173679.html\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121105044812/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-51173679.html\n | url-status = dead\n | archive-date = 5 November 2012\n | title = US grant for Varendra Museum\n | newspaper = The Independent\n | location = Dhaka\n | author = M. Shafiullah\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n | date = 5 March 2002\n}}</ref>\n\n==Organization and administration==\nThe university is run according to the Rajshahi University Act of 1973.<ref name=\"rubpedia\">{{cite book\n|last=Rahman |first=Mahbubar |year=2012\n|chapter=University of Rajshahi |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=University_of_Rajshahi\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second\n|publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref> The act, passed in 1973, allows the university considerably more autonomy than most other peer institutions. The president of Bangladesh is the de facto [[chancellor (education)|chancellor]], but his role is mainly ceremonial. The highest official after the chancellor is the vice-chancellor, selected by the [[senate]] of the university every four years. The vice-chancellor, as of June 2017, is [[M. Abdus Sobhan]].\n\nOther important officers include the [[Pro-Vice-Chancellor|pro vice-chancellor]], the [[Registrar (education)|registrar]], the controller of examinations and the proctor.<ref name=\"rubpedia\"/> The proctor is in direct charge of student activities and is the official with most direct contact with the students. The most important statutory bodies of the university are the senate, the academic council and the syndicate.<ref name=\"rubpedia\"/>\n\nAs a public institution, most of Rajshahi University's funding comes from the government. The University Grants Commission (UGC) is the body responsible for allocating funds to all [[public universities]].\n\nStudents are admitted after they pass the Higher Secondary Exam (HSC exam). In earlier days students partook in entrance examinations, a separate one for each department. But now students need to partake under unit of different faculty.<ref name=\"admit_1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.varsityadmission.com/Circular/Bachelor/University/Rajshahi_University.php |title=Admission Circular |website=Varsity Admission |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222505/http://www.varsityadmission.com/Circular/Bachelor/University/Rajshahi_University.php |archive-date=27 September 2007 |accessdate=10 October 2006\n}}</ref> This has been a contentious issue,<ref name=\"admit_2\">{{cite web\n| author = The Daily Star\n| publisher = University of Rajshahi | url=http://www.thedailystar.net/magazine/2006/10/02/news.htm\n| title=The State of Higher Education\n| accessdate=10 October 2006\n}}</ref> as there used to be only one exam for each faculty, after which students would be allocated to departments according to their result and choice of program.\n\nThe public University of Rajshahi's tuition fees are relatively low; nevertheless, a hike in admission fees, during the 2006\u201307 session, drew criticism from student bodies.<ref name=\"admit_3\">{{cite news\n| newspaper = The Daily Star | url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2007/03/12/d70312060376.htm| title=RU increases admission and certificate fees| accessdate=10 March 2007 | date = 12 March 2007\n}}</ref> As of 2007, the university awarded a total of 340 scholarships, whose annual value is around 1.1&nbsp;million taka. In addition, there are merit awards given by residential halls, departments and the university itself. Students are eligible for the [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]]'s Gold Medal award.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |author=BSS, Dhaka |author2= |title= Khaleda urges teachers, students: Maintain campus peace |url=http://newsfrombangladesh.net/view.php?hidRecord=59032 |publisher=News from Bangladesh |issn=1563-9304 |date= 31 August 2005|accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nAll colleges of the northern and southern regions of the country used to be affiliated with University of Rajshahi. However, the administration of colleges across the country was taken over by the National University when it was established in 1992.<ref name=\"NUpedia\">{{cite book\n|last1=Hossain |first1=Md Anawar |last2=Khanam |first2=Mobashera |year=2012\n|chapter=National University |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=National_University\n|editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A.\n|title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]\n}}</ref>\n\n===List of vice-chancellors===\nFollowing is the complete list of the vice-chancellors:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ru.ac.bd/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=68&Itemid=337 | title=Vice-Chancellor's Office | publisher=University of Rajshahi | accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n# [[Itrat Husain Zuberi]] (6 July 1953 \u2013 30 September 1957)\n# [[Momtazuddin Ahmed]] (1 October 1957 \u2013 30 August 1965)\n# [[Muhammad Shamsul Huq]] (31 August 1965 \u2013 4 August 1969)\n# [[Syed Sajjad Hussain]] (5 August 1969 \u2013 18 July 1971)\n# [[Muhammad Abdul Bari (academic)|Muhammad Abdul Bari]] (19 July 1971 \u2013 8 January 1972)\n# [[Khan Sarwar Murshid]] (1 February 1972 \u2013 3 August 1974)\n# [[Mazharul Islam (poet)|Mazharul Islam]] (4 August 1974 \u2013 18 September 1975)\n# [[Syed Ali Ahsan]] (27 September 1975 \u2013 22 June 1977)\n# [[Muhammad Abdul Bari (academic)|Muhammad Abdul Bari]] (7 July 1977 \u2013 17 February 1981)\n# Makbular Rahman Sarkar (26 February 1981 \u2013 22 February 1982)\n# Moslem Huda (22 February 1982 \u2013 20 September 1982)\n# Abdul Rakib (4 October 1982 - 19 March 1988)\n# Amanullah Ahmed (20 March 1988 \u2013 22 July 1992)\n# M. Anisur Rahman (22 July 1992 \u2013 22 August 1994)\n# M. Yusuf Ali (22 August 1994 \u2013 16 February 1997)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-138572|title=Prof Yusuf terms Liberation War 'civil war'|date=2010-05-15|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-06-14|language=en}}</ref>\n# Abdul Khaleque (17 February 1997 \u2013 3 August 1999)\n# [[M. Sayeedur Rahman Khan]] (4 August 1999 \u2013 13 November 2001)\n# Faisul Islam Farouqui (13 November 2001 \u2013 5 June 2005)\n# Md. Altaf Hossain (5 June 2005 \u2013 15 May 2008)\n# Mumnunul Keramat (acting) (16 May 2008 \u2013 28 February 2009)\n# [[M Abdus Sobhan]] (26 February 2009 \u2013 25 February 2013)\n# [[Muhammad Mizanuddin]] (19 March 2013 \u2013 20 March 2017)\n# [[M Abdus Sobhan]] (7 May 2017 \u2013 present)\n\n==Faculties and departments==\n\n{| style='float:right;font-size: 90%;border:1px solid #dddddd; background-color:#fefefe; padding:3px;margin:1em'\n|\n<span style='font-size: 95%'>'''Faculties'''</span>\n* Faculty of Science\n* Faculty of Engineering\n* Faculty of Arts\n* Faculty of Social Science\n* Faculty of Business Studies\n* Faculty of Life & Earth Science\n* Faculty of Law\n* Faculty of Agriculture\n* Faculty of Medicine\n* Faculty of Fine Arts\n\n[[Image:First Science Building, University of Rajshahi.JPG|thumb|left|The Faculty of Engineering: [[Royal Poinciana|Krishnachura]] blossoms in front of the First Science building that houses Physics and Applied Physics & Electronic Engineering]]\n|}\n\nThe university's 58 departments are organised into 10 [[Faculty (division)|faculties]]: Arts, Law, Science, Medicine, Business Studies, Social Sciences, Life and Earth Sciences, Fine Arts and Agriculture.<ref name=\"facultyref\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/faculty.htm\n | title = Faculties of University of Rajshahi\n | website = University of Rajshahi\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090826003410/http://www.ru.ac.bd/faculty.htm\n | archive-date = 26 August 2009\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n}}</ref> The Arts and the Law faculties are the oldest, both established in 1953, closely followed by the Faculty of Science (1956) and the Faculty of Engineering (est. 2009). The university's departments represent the traditional studies in arts, commerce, sciences and engineering through programs such as [[English studies|English]],History, [[Languages]] and [[Linguistics]], Economics, [[Business Studies]], [[Mathematics]], [[Applied Mathematics]] (est.2002), [[Physics]], [[Computer Science & Engineering]], [[Chemistry]], Statistics, Geology & Mining, [[Geography]], [[Psychology]], [[Zoology]], [[Botany]], etc. The university is increasingly emphasising more specialised programs such as [[Pharmacy]], [[Biochemistry]], [[Information engineering (field)|Information]] and [[Communication Engineering]] (ICE) (est. 2000), [[Genetics]] and [[Breeding in the wild|breeding]] (est. 1996).<ref name=\"profile\"/>\n\n===Faculty of Life and Earth Science===\nProminent departments in the faculty of [[Life Sciences|Life]] and [[Earth Sciences]] are\n\n# Geography and Environmental Studies\n# [[Psychology]]\n# [[Botany]]\n# [[Zoology]]\n# Geology & Mining\n# Genetic Engineering & Biotechnology\n# [[Clinical Psychology]]\n\n===Faculty of Arts===\nProminent departments in the faculty of [[Arts]] are\n\n#Department of English\n#Department of Bangla\n#Department of History\n#Department of Islamic History and Culture\n# Islamic Studies\n# Arabic\n# [[Sanskrit]]\n# Urdu\n# Persian Language and Literature\n\n===Faculty of Law===\nThe Faculty of Law has the following departments:\n# Department of Law, University of Rajshahi\n# Department of Law and Land Administration\n\nThe Department of Law is one of the pioneer institutes for graduate level legal education in Bangladesh as well as in South Asia. It was the first institution in South Asia that offered B.Jur. Honours (Bachelor of Jurisprudence). Now it offers LLB (Honours), LLM, Evening LLM, MPhil and PhD in the field of Law. It has a great number of alumni around the world including former president, chief justice, ministers and many of former and current judges of the apex courts of Bangladesh. This is one of the most demandable choice for the High school/college students of Bangladesh.\n\nThe Department of Law and Land Administration was established in the session of 2015-16. It is the pioneer department in Bangladesh as well as in the world in the field of education on Laws relating to land administration, land management and land survey. All core courses of Law are taught here. Graduates of this discipline can apply for all jobs which are for Law graduates, including the positions of Assistant Judge and Judicial Magistrate. They are able to practise as both civil and criminal lawyers and also as Income Tax lawyers. In addition, they are able to apply for jobs in the field of land administration/management. It is currently under a consideration that a separate BCS Cadre (Land) may be created and graduates from this discipline will only be able to apply for those jobs. The programmes offered by this Department include LLB (Honours), LLM, MPhil and PhD.\n \nThese two departments operate through a separate faculty - the Faculty of Law. Initiatives are under process  to establish a new department on the field of Corporate law under this faculty which is going to be the first institution for graduate level education in this field within Bangladesh.\n\nThis faculty is well known for the innovative environment on its premises. A huge library facility is provided here for the students and researchers. This institution provides a great chance to work with some of the greatest legal scholars of this country. The Bangladesh code was developed and was given a great shape for practical use under the leadership of a former chairman of this department in 2006.\n\nStudents of this institution are also popular for their extra-curricular activities. One of the leading debating clubs of the campus belongs to this department. Having a great tradition of mooting, and some nationally popular great legal practitioners as alumni, its Mooting Club RUMCS is well recognised and reputed in Bangladesh.\n\n===Faculty of Engineering===\nThe Faculty of Engineering include the following departments\n# [[Information engineering (field)|Information]] and Communication Engineering (ICE) (est. 2000)\n# Computer Science & Engineering\n# [[Applied Chemistry]] & [[Chemical Engineering]]\n# Materials Science and Engineering\n# Electrical and Electronic Engineering (EEE) (est. 2015)\n\nIn the late 1990 and 2000s, programs in computer science & engineering and Information & Communication Engineering were introduced. The newest addition to the Faculty of Engineering is the Department of Electrical and Electronic Engineering in 2015. The university used to have a separate engineering program through BIT (Bangladesh Institute of Technology) Rajshahi, which has become an independent university: [[Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology]] in 2002. University authorities have decided to merge Applied physics and electronic engineering department with electrical and electronic engineering department on 5 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/58197/ru-to-merge-apee-eee-depts|title=RU to merge APEE, EEE depts|date=2018-12-07 |accessdate=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://somoynews.tv/pages/details/%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%8F%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%AD%E0%A7%82%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%B9%E0%A6%9A%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%9B%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%87-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AD%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%97|title=\u09b0\u09be\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09c7 \u098f\u0995\u09c0\u09ad\u09c2\u09a4 \u09b9\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7 \u09a6\u09c1\u0987 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ad\u09be\u0997\n|date=2018-12-06 |accessdate=2019-06-22}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty of Social Science===\n\nThe Social Science Faculty has the following departments:\n\n# Economics\n# Political Science\n# Social Work\n# Sociology\n# Mass Communication and Journalism\n# Information Science & Library Management\n# Public Administration\n# Anthropology\n# Folklore\n# International Relations<ref name=\"deptinfo\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.ru.ac.bd/?page_id=722\n | title = Departments of University of Rajshahi\n | publisher = University of Rajshahi\n | accessdate = 14 July 2006\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Faculty of Business Studies ===\nFaculty of Business Studies has following departments:\n\n# [[Finance]]\n# Accounting & Information Systems\n# [[Marketing]]\n# [[Management Studies]]\n# Banking & Insurance\n# Tourism & Hospitality Management\n\nAll of these departments are in the Rabindra Building.\n\n===Faculty of Science===\nFaculty of Science has the following departments:\n\n# Mathematics\n# Physics\n# Chemistry\n# Statistics\n# Biochemistry & Molecular Biology\n# Pharmacy\n# [[Department of Population Science and Human Resource Development|Population Science & Human Resource Development]]\n# Applied Mathematics\n# Physical Education and Sports Sciences\n\nMost of these departments are in the 2nd, 3rd and 4th science buildings.\n\n===Faculty of Agriculture===\n\nFaculty of Agriculture has the following departments:\n\n# Agronomy and Agricultural Extension\n# Crop Science and Technology was established in 2005. It offers a 4-year [[Bachelor of Science in Agriculture|B.Sc.Ag.(Hons)]] degree and 18 months [[Master of Science|M.S.]] degree. [[M.Phil]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (Ph.D) degrees are also offered. About 250 students are studying in the department.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dept.ru.ac.bd/cst/?p=258 |title=Dept. of Crop Science and Technology |website=Crop Science & Technology}}</ref>\n# Fisheries\n# Veterinary & Animal Science\nAll of these department are in the Agricultural Faculty Building.  Only 'practical work' is performing in Narikelbaria Campus. Founded in 2000, the Faculty of [[Agricultural Science|Agriculture]] was formed when a local agricultural college was absorbed into the university.\n\n===Faculty of Medicine===\nThis faculty is organised differently from other disciplines. Medical education is provided by seven medical colleges located around Rajshahi Division and Khulna Division. Though these colleges are autonomous to a large extent, the degrees are conferred by Rajshahi University. [[Rajshahi Medical College]] is the oldest medical college under administration of the university and is a few miles west of the university campus along with the highly equipped 1000-bed [[Rajshahi Medical College Hospital]].\n\nGovernment medical colleges under the supervision of Rajshahi University:\n\n# [[Rajshahi Medical College]]\n# [[Pabna Medical College]]\n# [[Shaheed Ziaur Rahman Medical College]]\n# [[Rangpur Medical College]]\n# [[Dinajpur Medical College]]\n# [[Kushtia Medical College]]\n# [[Jessore Medical College]]\n# [[Khulna Medical College]]\n# [[Satkhira Medical College]]\n# Shaheed M. Munsur Ali Medical College, Sirajgonj\n# Institute of medical Technology, Rajshahi (BSPT)\n\n===Institutes===\nThere are six institutes of Rajshahi University.\n\n# Institutes of Bangladesh Studies\n# Institutes of Biological Science\n# Institute of Business Administration\n# Institute of Education and Research\n# Institute of Environmental Science\n# Institute of English and Other Languages\n\n==Affiliating colleges under Rajshahi University==\n# BCMC college of ENGINEERING and TECHNOLOGY, Jessore\n# Rangpur Engineering College\n# International Institute of Applied Science & Technology, Rangpur\n# Tomaltola Agricultural College, Nator\n# South East Engineering College, Khulna\n# Epsilon Engineering College, Rajshahi\n# Rajshahi College of Science & Technology, Rajshahi\n# Khwaja Yunus Ali Medical College, Rajshahi\n# Islami Bank Medical College, Rajshahi\n# Barind Medical College, Rajshahi\n# TMSS Medical College, Bogra\n# Prime Medical College, Rangpur\n# Udoyon Dental College, Rajshahi\n# Institute of Health Technology, Rajshahi\n# Northern Medical College, Rangpur\n# Rangpur Dental College\n# Bangladesh Police Academy, Sardah, Rajshahi\n# Imperial College of Engineering, Khulna\n#South-East Engineering College, Khulna\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Housing===\n\nThe university has 18 residential halls for students, six for women and eleven for men and one International Dormitory. The halls are named after prominent Bangladeshi historical and cultural figures, some of them from Rajshahi. The largest men's hall is Shahid Habibur Rahman Hall, named after a mathematics professor killed on campus during the 1971 war by the Pakistani Army. The largest women's hall is Monnujan Hall, followed by Begum Rokeya Hall, named after [[Rokeya Sakhawat Hussain]], a leading figure in women's rights activism in Bengal.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\nThe housing system can accommodate  more than 10,000 students, which has created a deepening accommodation crisis as the student body has risen to 25,000.<ref name=\"BDToday\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ru.ac.bd/administration/paper.htm|title=University of Rajshahi |accessdate=29 April 2008 |author=  |date=5 August 2005 |year= |work=Glorious 52 years |publisher=The Bangladesh Today   |pages= }}</ref> Apart from the seat limitations, the amenities of these halls do not always meet decent accommodation standards.<ref name=\"amen_1\">{{cite news\n| author = S.M. Humayun Kabir\n| newspaper = New Age\n| url=http://www.newagebd.com/2005/jun/09/met.html\n| title=Students live with poor amenities at University of Rajshahi | accessdate=10 October 2006 | date = 5 June 2005\n}}</ref> This has led to the establishment of many privately owned off-campus \"[[mess]]es\". The residential halls provide meals, which are subsidised by the university authorities.\n\n====Names of halls====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!No\n! Name\n!Name of Provosts\n!PABX Telephone\n|-\n|01\n|Sher-e-Bangla Fazlul Haque Hall\n|Mostofa Tarequl Ahsan\n|4191\n|-\n|02\n|Shah Makhdum Hall\n|M. Zahangir Alam\n|4193\n|-\n|03\n|Nawab Abdul Latif Hall\n| Bipul Kumar Biswas\n|4195\n|-\n|04\n|Syed Amir Ali Hall\n|Golam Mortuza\n|4194\n|-\n|05\n|Shahid Shamsuzzoha Hall\n|Dr.M.Julkar naeen\n\n|-\n|06\n|Shahid Habibur Rahman Hall\n|Prof. Abdur Rahman\n|4200\n|-\n|07\n|Motihar Hall\n|Afrouzzaman Khan Chowdhury\n|4192\n|-\n|08\n|Madar Baksh Hall\n|M. Abdur Rahim Khan\n|4198\n|-\n|09\n|Shahid Sohrawardi Hall\n|M.Robiul \n|4197\n|-\n|10\n|Shahid Ziaur Rahman Hall\n|A.N.M. Zahangir Kabir\n|4199\n|-\n|11\n|Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Hall\n|Mohd. Nurul Islam\n|4190\n|-\n|12\n|Monnujan Hall\n|Irin Banu Luci\n|4204\n|-\n|13\n|Begum Rokeya Hall\n|Nazma Afroz\n|4202\n|-\n|14\n|Tapashi Rabeya Hall\n|Hosne Ara Jesmin\n|4201\n|-\n|15\n|Begum Khaleda Zia Hall\n|Salma Banu\n|4203\n|-\n|16\n|Rahamatunnesa Hall\n|Mele Jesmin\n|4205\n|-\n|17\n|Bongomata Sheikh Fazilatun-nesa Hall\n|Fahima Khatun\n|711206\n|-\n|18\n|Shaheed Mir Abdul Qauyum Int\u2019l Dormitory\n|\n|711237\n|}\n\n===Activities===\n\nThe physical education department of the university has 27 instructors and is equipped with a 25,000-seat stadium, two gymnasiums, one swimming pool, four [[association football|football]] grounds, one hockey ground, four tennis courts, two basketball courts and a squash court.\n\nThe Teacher Students Center was designed to be the centre of cultural activities of the university. Reception of fresh students, celebration of national holidays, and the annual cultural competition are key cultural events at the campus.<ref name=\"rubpedia\" /> The university is home to recitation groups like ''Shwanan'', and drama groups like ''Anushilon'' and Rajshahi University Drama Association (RUDA).<ref name=\"drama_1\">{{cite news\n| newspaper = New Age\n| url=http://www.newagebd.com/2006/jul/07/met.html\n| title=53rd founding anniversary of RU observed\n| accessdate=17 March 2007\n| date = 7 July 2006\n}}</ref> A vibrant fine arts scene thrives around the Department of Fine Arts, and the campus hosts exhibitions each year. The university has branches of all major national cultural groups, including Udichi and ''Gono Natto Shongstha''.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\nDuring the three major national days \u2014 [[Language Movement Day]] (21 February), [[Bangladeshi Independence Day|Independence Day]] (26 March) and [[Victory Day (Bangladesh)|Victory Day]] (16 December) \u2014  the university hosts public meetings, cultural programs and political activities. On these days, students and teachers, going barefoot, congregate around the Shaheed Minar and pay their respect. During the major Muslim religious occasions of [[Muslim holidays|Eid]], the university is usually deserted as students go home to be with their families. Other religiously important days like [[Mid-Sha'ban|Shabe-barat]] are observed through discussions and religious activities. The major Hindu festival celebrated in the university is [[Saraswati Puja]]\u2014[[Saraswati]], the [[goddess]] of knowledge, is worshiped in a central location as well as individually in many residential halls.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} The Bengali new year, ''[[Pohela Baisakh]]'' is also observed with much pomp.<ref name=\"nobobarsho_1\">{{cite news\n| newspaper =New Age| url=http://www.newagebd.com/2006/apr/16/met.html| title=Grand celebrations in Rajshahi | accessdate=10 October 2006\n| date = 16 April 2006\n}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* Physicist [[Arun Kumar Basak]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dept.ru.ac.bd/physics/faculty/current-faculty-members/|title=Current Faculty Members |work=Rajshahi University |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Former Minister Mr Narayan Chandra Chanda MP\n* Former State Minister for Home affairs-[[Shamsul Hoque Tuku]] MP\n* Singer [[Farida Parveen]]\n* Singer [[Andrew Kishor]]\n* Cricketer [[Al-Amin Hossain]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Isam |first=Mohammad |date=14 August 2014 |title=Hard work nothing new to Al-Amin |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/769977.html |work=ESPNcricinfo |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Writer [[Selina Hossain]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barguna.gov.bd/node/497952-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%96%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AC- |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519023347/http://www.barguna.gov.bd/node/497952-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%96%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AC- |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 May 2015 |script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09bf\u0996\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a4 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac |trans-title=Famous personalities |website=Bangladesh National Portal |language=bn |access-date=24 March 2017 }}</ref>\n* Writer [[Hasan Azizul Huq]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Mahfuj |first=Emran |date=5 July 2015 |title='Bangalis are trying to get ahead by forgetting the past' |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/op-ed/bangalis-are-trying-get-ahead-forgetting-the-past-107530 |newspaper=The Daily Star |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Physicist [[M. Sayeedur Rahman Khan]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ru.ac.bd/vc/?page_id=44 |title=List of former Vice Chancellor |website=University of Rajshahi |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Poet [[Mahadev Saha]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mahadevsaha.com/ |title=Mahadev Saha |website=Mahadev Saha |access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Director [[Giasuddin Selim]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-203688 |title=Giasuddin Selim: How to bring about a revolution in Bangladeshi filmdom |newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n* Playwright [[Malay Bhowmick]]\n\n==Incidents and controversies==\nDuring the 1980s, the four-year honours course took as long as eight years due to the session backlogs, resulting mainly from conflicts between factions of political groups. Since the early 1990s, [[student politics]] has been comparatively calmer, with student body elections not being held for more than a decade. The student groups have been demanding elections whereas others feel student politics should be banned.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn late 2004 and early 2005, two professors of Rajshahi University got assassinated within three months: Professor Yunus from the Economics department in December 2004<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |author= |author2= |title= 90 RU teachers want VC to quit over Taher killing |url=http://www.newagebd.com/2006/mar/04/nat.html |newspaper=New Age|id= |date= 4 March 2006|accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> and Professor Taher from the Geology and Mining department in February 2005.<ref name=\"Taher\">{{cite news |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/print_news.php?nid=37686 |title=Verdict in RU Prof Taher murder case today |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=22 May 2008 |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> Both murders were suspected to be driven by political motivations. In 2006, the commander of [[Jamaat-ul-Mujahideen Bangladesh|Jama'atul Mujahideen Bangladesh]] admitted to the [[Rapid Action Battalion|RAB]] interrogators that his operatives carried out the attack on Yunus, as well as the 2004 attack on writer [[Humayun Azad]], the murder of another writer, bomb blasts, and attacks on cinemas.<ref>{{cite news |date=5 June 2006 |title=JMB also killed writer of Tangail |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2006/06/05/d6060501128.htm |newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\nAround the same time, a controversy over the hiring of over 500 new employees broke; detractors suggested that they were hired illegally, either in return for money or for political reasons.<ref name=\"corruption_1\">{{cite news | title=Recruitment in RU postponed amid employees' agitation | url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2006/10/08/d6100801127.htm | newspaper = Daily Star | date = 8 October 2006 | accessdate=10 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nSince the new millennium, much attention has been focused on politics among university teaching staff. Observers have claimed that the teaching staff have been thoroughly polarised according to party lines in national politics.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\nIn 2005, [[Muhammad Asadullah Al-Ghalib]] of the university was arrested for links with the [[Ahle Hadith Andolon Bangladesh]], but was acquitted in 2008.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn August 2007, six detained professors of the university were temporarily suspended for their involvement in organising protests for restoring that violated Emergency Power Rules,<ref>{{cite news | title=RU suspends its 6 detained teachers\n| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/story.php?nid=2997 | newspaper = Daily Star | date = 24 February 2005 | accessdate=10 March 2007\n}}</ref> though they were discharged later from allegations and returned to the university with proper honour.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn November 2017, a woman student was abducted from the university campus, sparking protests by students demanding her rescue and improved security on the campus.<ref name=\"protesting_2018_11_18_daily_sun_com\">[http://www.daily-sun.com/post/269497/Rajshahi-University-students-besiege-VC%E2%80%99s-residence-protesting-student-abduction \"Rajshahi University students besiege VC\u2019s residence protesting student abduction,\"] November 18, 2017, ''Daily Sun'' ('''daily-sun.com'''), Bangladesh</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, protests and counter-violence erupted at various universities, particularly RU, over the \"[[Bangladesh Quota Reform Protests 2018|quota reform movement]],\" which sought to change the quota system that allocated 56% of Bangladesh government jobs to specific \"entitled\" classes. RU's vice-chancellor, Professor M. Abdus Sobhan, dismissed the quota-reform movement as an \"anti-government movement with a motive to carry out sabotage.\"<ref name=\"rajshahi_police_2018_07_09_thedailystar_net\">[https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/rajshahi-police-saw-nothing-1602220 \"Rajshahi police saw nothing!\"], July 9, 2018 ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]]'', Bangladesh</ref>\n\nRU student and quota-reform movement leader Toriqul Islam, and 15 others, were attacked during their protest march, July 2, 2018, by opposing students. A prominent Bangladesh newspaper, the ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]],'' which filmed the incident, identified 10 of the attackers as leaders and activists of the [[Bangladesh Chhatra League]] (BCL), a pro-[[Awami League]] (Bangladesh's ruling party) student organisation.  Video footage and photos published in Bangladeshi media showed BCL men\u2014with sticks, bamboo poles, a dagger and a hammer\u2014beating Toriqul, who suffered a broken leg and severe head injury. Several police officers standing nearby (unaware the incident was being filmed) did not intervene until the attack was finished, then took the victim to hospital\u2014but without arresting any of the attackers, publicly denying it was anything more than a \"scuffle.\" University authorities declined to investigate, for lack of a filed complaint. Images of the attack, distributed on social media, sparked widespread criticism over police and university administration inaction.<ref name=\"rajshahi_police_2018_07_09_thedailystar_net\" /><ref name=\"injured_quota_protester_2018_07_08_dhaka_tribune\">[https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2018/07/08/injured-quota-reform-activist-tariqul-being-moved-to-dhaka-for-treatment \"Injured quota protester Tariqul moved to Dhaka,\"] July 8, 2018, ''[[Dhaka Tribune]]''</ref><ref name=\"quota_reform_activist_2018_07_06_prothomalo_com\">[http://en.prothomalo.com/bangladesh/news/179205/Quota-reform-activist-Toriqul-denied-treatment-in \"Quota reform activist Toriqul denied treatment in govt hospital,\"] July 6, 2018, ''[[Daily Prothom Alo]]''</ref><ref name=\"injured_ru_quota_reformist_2018_07_08_prothomalo_com\">[http://en.prothomalo.com/bangladesh/news/179318/Injured-RU-quota-reformist-Tariqul-being-brought \"Injured RU quota reformist Toriqul being brought to Dhaka,\"] July 8, 2018, ''[[Daily Prothom Alo]]''</ref>\n\nDespite student Toriqul's unresolved major injuries, the university's [[Rajshahi Medical College]] Hospital discharged him July 5, 2018, forcing his doctor to arrange for immediate surgery elsewhere.<ref name=\"quota_reform_activist_2018_07_06_prothomalo_com\" /><ref name=\"injured_ru_quota_reformist_2018_07_08_prothomalo_com\" /><ref name=\"injured_toriqul_2018_07_09_thedailystar_net\">[https://www.thedailystar.net/country/injured-quota-reform-leader-toriqul-islam-being-brought-to-dhaka-from-rajshahi-better-treatment-1601917 \"Injured quota reform leader Toriqul Islam being brought to Dhaka,\"] July 8, 2018 ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]]'', Bangladesh</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"120px\">\nParis road rajshahi.JPG|Paris Road\nMedical Center, University of Rajshahi (1).jpg|Medical Center\nRailline, inside of rajshahi university.jpg|Rail Line\nRajshahi University Shaheed Minar, Rajshahi.jpg|Shaheed Minar\nRajshahi University Stadium.jpg|Stadium\nSwiming phool, rajshahi university.jpg|Swimming Pool\nMain gate of university of rajshahi.jpg|Main Gate\nTSCC, University of Rajshahi (1).jpg|TSCC\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Bangladesh}}\n{{Commons category|University of Rajshahi}}\n* [[List of universities in Bangladesh]]\n* [[Islamic University of Technology]] (IUT)\n* [[Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology]] (BUET)\n* [[University of Dhaka]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n\n