An aerial look at the Alberta Tar Sands]\n* G.R. Gray, R. Luhning: [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/bitumen/ Bitumen] ''The Canadian Encyclopedia''\n* [[Jiri Rezac]], [http://www.jirirezac.com/stories/oilsands/ Alberta Oilsands]  photo story and aerials\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090205150634/http://citizen.nfb.ca/tar-sands ''Exploring the Alberta tar sands'', Citizenshift, National Film Board of Canada]\n* [http://www.democracynow.org/2010/6/25/tar_sands Indigenous Groups Lead Struggle Against Canada\u2019s Tar Sands]&nbsp;\u2013 video report by ''[[Democracy Now!]]''\n* [https://doi.org/10.1007%2FBF02654468 Extraction of vanadium from oil sands]\n* {{cite magazine|last=Hoffman |first=Carl |date=1 October 2009 |title=New Tech to Tap North America's Vast Oil Reserves |magazine=Popular Mechanics |url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/engineering/4212552}}\n* [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R42537.pdf Canadian Oil Sands: Life-Cycle Assessments of Greenhouse Gas Emissions] [[Congressional Research Service]]\n* [http://osip.alberta.ca Alberta Government Oil Sands Information Portal] Interactive Map and Data Library\n\n{{Petroleum industry}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oil Sands}}\n[[Category:Bituminous sands| ]]\n[[Category:Petroleum geology]]\n[[Category:Petroleum industry]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Twozerooz", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed biased source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oil_sands"}
{"title_page": "Death to False Metal", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Death to False Metal\n| type       = compilation\n| artist     = [[Weezer]]\n| cover      = Death to False Metal cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2010|11|02}}\n| recorded   = 1993\u20132010\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n| length     = 32:52\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| producer   =\n* Weezer\n* [[Rick Rubin]]\n* [[Shawn Everett]]\n* [[Rivers Cuomo]]\n| prev_title = [[Hurley (album)|Hurley]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[Everything Will Be Alright in the End]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n\n'''''Death to False Metal''''' is a compilation album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Weezer]], released on November 2, 2010 by [[Geffen Records]]. The album comprises several previously unreleased tracks from throughout Weezer's career, with vocalist and guitarist [[Rivers Cuomo]] stating that the songs together make an album that should \"logically follow ''[[Hurley (album)|Hurley]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kroq.radio.com/2010/10/12/weezer-set-to-release-hurley-follow-up-album-in-november/ |title=Weezer Set To Release \"Hurley\" Follow-up Album In November |publisher=KROQ FM |date=2010-10-12 |accessdate=2018-04-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111074637/http://kroq.radio.com/2010/10/12/weezer-set-to-release-hurley-follow-up-album-in-november/ |archivedate=2011-01-11 }}</ref> The album debuted at number 48 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.billboard.com/music/weezer/chart-history/TLP|title=Weezer Chart History: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate = 2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nThe album was released simultaneously with the deluxe edition of the band's second studio album, ''[[Pinkerton (album)|Pinkerton]]'' (1996). The title comes from a phrase coined by [[Manowar]].\n\n==Background and recording==\nOriginally known as ''Odds and Ends'', the album was first mentioned by guitarist [[Brian Bell]] during the summer of 2008. Vocalist and guitarist [[Rivers Cuomo]] states that the tracks are \"great songs, great recordings, but for some reason they didn't make the final cut for a record. And like the ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo|Alone]]'' record, they span a vast period of time from the very beginning of our career in the early '90s right up to the present day.\"\n\nFrontman [[Rivers Cuomo]] considers ''Death to False Metal'' to be Weezer's ninth studio album. Band webmaster and historian Karl Koch describes the release differently as \"a special album, [...] sort of like Weezer's version of Rivers' ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo|Alone]]'' records.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weezer.com/profiles/blogs/20101012-death-to-false-metal |title=2010/10/12 Death To False Metal! |publisher=Weezer |date=2010-10-12 |accessdate=2011-07-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718233445/http://weezer.com/profiles/blogs/20101012-death-to-false-metal |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref>\n\nThe version of \"Mykel & Carli\" on the iTunes version of the album differs from the previously released version on the \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\" single in 1994 and later the deluxe edition of the band's [[Weezer (The Blue Album)|self-titled 1994 debut]]. It has been speculated by fans that it is the original 1993 recording of the song from The Blue Album sessions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://classic.weezer.com/info/recording/WeezRecHist5.htm |title=Weezer Recording History Page 5 |accessdate=2010-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718023121/http://classic.weezer.com/info/recording/WeezRecHist5.htm |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref> with the more common previously released version known to have been recorded in the summer of 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://classic.weezer.com/info/recording/WeezRecHist6.htm |title=Weezer Recording History Page 6 |accessdate=2010-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718023158/http://classic.weezer.com/info/recording/WeezRecHist6.htm |archivedate=2011-07-18 }} \"Mykel and Carli (appeared on many foreign singles, plus the \"Hear You Me!\" compilation)\"</ref>\n\nThe album's opening track, \"[[Turning Up the Radio]]\", is the product of [[Rivers Cuomo]]'s [[YouTube]] songwriting project ''[[Rivers Cuomo#Other projects|Let's Write a Sawng]]'', a process where the frontman curated a 15-step program where people were free to submit ideas such as titles, chord progressions and melodies to create a collaborative song through the video-sharing platform. The resulting song has seventeen co-writers and involves tracks recorded across various locations.<ref>{{cite book |last= Starko |first=Alane Jordan |date= September 19, 2017|title=Creativity in the Classroom: Schools of Curious Delight |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Zno2DwAAQBAJ |publisher=Routledge |isbn= }}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2014 it was announced that the album would be available on vinyl for the first time.<ref>http://diffuser.fm/weezer-to-finally-release-death-to-false-metal-on-vinyl/</ref>\n\nThe cover art for the album mimics that of a religious tract from [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] featuring an artist's impression of a perfect planet Earth.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 56/100<ref name=MC>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/death-to-false-metal |title=Death to False Metal Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More at Metacritic |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2012-05-04}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|title=Review: ''Death to False Metal'' |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2037917|pure_url=yes}} |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=5 November 2010}}</ref>\n| rev2 = Alter the Press!\n| rev2score = 4/5<ref>{{cite web|last=Reid |first=Sean |url=http://www.alterthepress.com/2010/11/album-review-weezer-death-to-false.html |title=Album Review: Weezer - Death To False Metal |website=Alter the Press! |date=2009-08-20 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1068450/weezer-death-to-false-metal |title=Weezer, \"Death to False Metal\" |work=Billboard |date=2010-11-15 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/10/album-review-weezer-death-to-false-metal/ |title=Album Review: Weezer \u2013 Death to False Metal |website=Consequence of Sound |date=2010-10-18 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n| rev5score = 4/10<ref name=DiN>{{cite web|last=Wood |first=Marie |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/15797/reviews/4141503 |title=Weezer - Death to False Metal / Releases / Releases // Drowned In Sound |website=[[Drowned in Sound]] |date=2010-11-11 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Hot Press]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Seoige |first=Eamonn |url=http://www.hotpress.com/music/reviews/albums/7339668.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228025516/http://www.hotpress.com/music/reviews/albums/7339668.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-12-28 |title=Death to False Metal|website=[[Hot Press]] |date=2010-02-11}}</ref>\n| rev7 = [[IGN]]\n| rev7score = 7.5/10<ref name=IGN>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/11/04/weezer-death-to-false-metal-review |title=Weezer: Death To False Metal Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=2010-11-04 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev8 = InYourSpeakers\n| rev8score = 52/100<ref>{{cite web |first=Joseph |last=Bogen |title=InYourSpeakers: Reviews: Weezer: Death to False Metal |url=http://inyourspeakers.com/content/review/weezer-death-false-metal-11102010 |date=10 November 2010 |accessdate=23 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113956/http://inyourspeakers.com/content/review/weezer-death-false-metal-11102010 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev9score = 3.5/10<ref name=Pitchfork>{{cite web |first=Ian|last=Cohen|title=Album Reviews: Weezer: Pinkerton (Deluxe Edition) / Death to False Metal|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14817-pinkerton-deluxe-edition-death-to-false-metal/|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=15 November 2010}}</ref>\n| rev10 = Punknews.org\n| rev10score = {{rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |first=Tori |last=Pederson |title=Weezer - Death to False Metal|url=https://www.punknews.org/review/9966/weezer-death-to-false-metal|website=Punknews.org|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to [[Metacritic]], ''Death to False Metal'' has received mixed reviews, receiving an average score of 56/100.<ref name=MC/>\n\n[[AllMusic]] gave the album 4 out of 5 stars, saying \"It's a wonder why a few of these cuts didn't pop up before this, but as a collection of outtakes, they hold together better than some of the band's proper albums.\"<ref name=AllMusic/> ''[[Drowned in Sound]]'' gave it a 4 out of 10, calling it \"lineage of dumbed down music to even more dumb lyrics\", citing songs such as \"Blowin' My Stack\" and \"Trampoline\".<ref name=DiN/> [[IGN]] gave it a 7.5 out of 10, citing \"...the album feels a lot more cohesive than similar rarities sets, though a little more diversity would have made for a more interesting listen.\"<ref name=IGN/>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Rivers Cuomo]], except where noted\n| total_length = 32:52\n| title1 = [[Turning Up the Radio]]\n| length1 = 3:37\n| note1 = Cuomo, Alfredo Robert Carballo, Paul Dutton, Patrick Gannon, Joshua Godinez, Daniel James Kelsch, Reshad Malik, Cameron L. Maris, Sam Mitchell, Taylor Morden, Daniel Powell, Lauren Sonder, Nishant Thakur, Justin Vail, Mike Danger, Kingsly Vanata & Ryan Wiesbrock\n| title2 = I Don't Want Your Loving\n| length2 = 3:03\n| title3 = Blowin' My Stack\n| length3 = 3:44\n| note3 = Cuomo, Brian Bell, Scott Shriner\n| title4 = Losing My Mind\n| length4 = 4:02\n| title5 = Everyone\n| length5 = 2:49\n| title6 = I'm a Robot\n| length6 = 2:31\n| title7 = Trampoline\n| length7 = 2:45\n| title8 = The Odd Couple\n| length8 = 3:07\n| title9 = Autopilot\n| length9 = 2:57\n| title10 = [[Un-Break My Heart|Unbreak My Heart]]\n| length10 = 4:11\n| note10 = [[Diane Warren]]\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = International bonus tracks\n| title11         = Yellow Camaro\n| note11          = Brian Bell\n| length11        = 1:54\n| title12         = Outta Here\n| length12        = 2:34\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline         = iTunes Store/Vinyl bonus track\n| title13          = Mykel and Carli \n| length13         = 3:13\n}}\n\n* \"Unbreak My Heart\" originally performed by [[Toni Braxton]].\n* \"Yellow Camaro\" exclusive Japanese track.\n* \"Mykel and Carli\" unreleased version from [[Weezer (1994 album)|''The Blue Album'''s]] sessions.\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/album/death-to-false-metal-mw0002059085/credits</ref>\n\n'''Weezer'''\n* [[Rivers Cuomo]] \u2013 lead vocals, guitar, keyboard\n* [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]] \u2013 drums, percussion\n* [[Brian Bell]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals, synth, keyboard\n* [[Scott Shriner]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n* [[David Campbell (American arranger/composer)|David Campbell]] \u2013 [[string section|string]] [[arrangement]]s, [[conductor (music)|conducting]]\n* [[Taylor Morden]] \u2013 [[guitar]], [[synthesizer]], backing vocals\n\n'''Design'''\n* [[Andy Mueller]] \u2013 art direction\n* [[Robert Pitt]] \u2013 cover painting, paintings\n* [[Daniel Field]], [[Karl Koch]], [[Sean Murphy]], [[Spike Jonze]] \u2013 [[photography]]\n\n{{col-2}}\n'''Production'''\n* [[Chad Bamford]] \u2013 [[engineer]]\n* [[Shawn Everett]] \u2013 engineer, [[mixing]]\n* [[Taylor Morden]] \u2013 engineer, [[production]]\n* [[Rich Mouser]] \u2013 engineer\n* [[Rick Rubin]] \u2013 engineer\n* [[Jim Scott]] \u2013 engineer\n* [[Dave Collins]]\u2013 [[mastering]]\n* [[Marc McClusky]] \u2013 [[mixing]] (tracks: 1 to 3)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the album, which is allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLC2qC-e5YikdrY8wDvnUTi6WYO1e58bqi ''Death to False Metal''] at [[YouTube]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n* {{metacritic album|death-to-false-metal}}\n* {{MusicBrainz release group|id=51c88244-97b3-4ae5-9ffa-3a4530bb6343|name=Death to False Metal}}\n\n{{Weezer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Death To False Metal}}\n[[Category:Weezer albums]]\n[[Category:2010 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:DGC Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Death to False Metal\n| type       = compilation\n| artist     = [[Weezer]]\n| cover      = Death to False Metal cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2010|11|02}}\n| recorded   = 1993\u20132010\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n| length     = 32:52\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| producer   =\n* Weezer\n* [[Rick Rubin]]\n* [[Shawn Everett]]\n* [[Rivers Cuomo]]\n| prev_title = [[Hurley (album)|Hurley]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[Everything Will Be Alright in the End]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n\n'''''Death to False Metal''''' is a compilation album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Weezer]], released on November 2, 2010 by [[Geffen Records]]. The album comprises several previously unreleased tracks from throughout Weezer's career, with vocalist and guitarist [[Rivers Cuomo]] stating that the songs together make an album that should \"logically follow ''[[Hurley (album)|Hurley]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kroq.radio.com/2010/10/12/weezer-set-to-release-hurley-follow-up-album-in-november/ |title=Weezer Set To Release \"Hurley\" Follow-up Album In November |publisher=KROQ FM |date=2010-10-12 |accessdate=2018-04-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111074637/http://kroq.radio.com/2010/10/12/weezer-set-to-release-hurley-follow-up-album-in-november/ |archivedate=2011-01-11 }}</ref> The album debuted at number 48 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.billboard.com/music/weezer/chart-history/TLP|title=Weezer Chart History: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate = 2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nThe album was released simultaneously with the deluxe edition of the band's second studio album, ''[[Pinkerton (album)|Pinkerton]]'' (1996). The title comes from a phrase coined by [[Manowar]].\n\n==Background and recording==\nOriginally known as ''Odds and Ends'', the album was first mentioned by guitarist [[Brian Bell]] during the summer of 2008. Vocalist and guitarist [[Rivers Cuomo]] states that the tracks are \"great songs, great recordings, but for some reason they didn't make the final cut for a record. And like the ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo|Alone]]'' record, they span a vast period of time from the very beginning of our career in the early '90s right up to the present day.\"\n\nFrontman [[Rivers Cuomo]] considers ''Death to False Metal'' to be Weezer's ninth studio album. Band webmaster and historian Karl Koch describes the release differently as \"a special album, [...] sort of like Weezer's version of Rivers' ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo|Alone]]'' records.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weezer.com/profiles/blogs/20101012-death-to-false-metal |title=2010/10/12 Death To False Metal! |publisher=Weezer |date=2010-10-12 |accessdate=2011-07-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718233445/http://weezer.com/profiles/blogs/20101012-death-to-false-metal |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref>\n\nThe version of \"Mykel & Carli\" on the iTunes version of the album differs from the previously released version on the \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\" single in 1994 and later the deluxe edition of the band's [[Weezer (The Blue Album)|self-titled 1994 debut]]. It has been speculated by fans that it is the original 1993 recording of the song from The Blue Album sessions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://classic.weezer.com/info/recording/WeezRecHist5.htm |title=Weezer Recording History Page 5 |accessdate=2010-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718023121/http://classic.weezer.com/info/recording/WeezRecHist5.htm |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref> with the more common previously released version known to have been recorded in the summer of 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://classic.weezer.com/info/recording/WeezRecHist6.htm |title=Weezer Recording History Page 6 |accessdate=2010-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718023158/http://classic.weezer.com/info/recording/WeezRecHist6.htm |archivedate=2011-07-18 }} \"Mykel and Carli (appeared on many foreign singles, plus the \"Hear You Me!\" compilation)\"</ref>\n\nThe album's opening track, \"[[Turning Up the Radio]]\", is the product of [[Rivers Cuomo]]'s [[YouTube]] songwriting project ''[[Rivers Cuomo#Other projects|Let's Write a Sawng]]'', a process where the frontman curated a 15-step program where people were free to submit ideas such as titles, chord progressions and melodies to create a collaborative song through the video-sharing platform. The resulting song has seventeen co-writers and involves tracks recorded across various locations.<ref>{{cite book |last= Starko |first=Alane Jordan |date= September 19, 2017|title=Creativity in the Classroom: Schools of Curious Delight |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Zno2DwAAQBAJ |publisher=Routledge |isbn= }}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2014 it was announced that the album would be available on vinyl for the first time.<ref>http://diffuser.fm/weezer-to-finally-release-death-to-false-metal-on-vinyl/</ref>\n\nThe cover art for the album mimics that of a religious tract from [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] featuring an artist's impression of a perfect planet Earth.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 56/100<ref name=MC>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/death-to-false-metal |title=Death to False Metal Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More at Metacritic |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2012-05-04}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|title=Review: ''Death to False Metal'' |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2037917|pure_url=yes}} |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=5 November 2010}}</ref>\n| rev2 = Alter the Press!\n| rev2score = 4/5<ref>{{cite web|last=Reid |first=Sean |url=http://www.alterthepress.com/2010/11/album-review-weezer-death-to-false.html |title=Album Review: Weezer - Death To False Metal |website=Alter the Press! |date=2009-08-20 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1068450/weezer-death-to-false-metal |title=Weezer, \"Death to False Metal\" |work=Billboard |date=2010-11-15 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/10/album-review-weezer-death-to-false-metal/ |title=Album Review: Weezer \u2013 Death to False Metal |website=Consequence of Sound |date=2010-10-18 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n| rev5score = 4/10<ref name=DiN>{{cite web|last=Wood |first=Marie |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/15797/reviews/4141503 |title=Weezer - Death to False Metal / Releases / Releases // Drowned In Sound |website=[[Drowned in Sound]] |date=2010-11-11 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Hot Press]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Seoige |first=Eamonn |url=http://www.hotpress.com/music/reviews/albums/7339668.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228025516/http://www.hotpress.com/music/reviews/albums/7339668.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-12-28 |title=Death to False Metal|website=[[Hot Press]] |date=2010-02-11}}</ref>\n| rev7 = [[IGN]]\n| rev7score = 7.5/10<ref name=IGN>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/11/04/weezer-death-to-false-metal-review |title=Weezer: Death To False Metal Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=2010-11-04 |accessdate=2013-07-07}}</ref>\n| rev8 = InYourSpeakers\n| rev8score = 52/100<ref>{{cite web |first=Joseph |last=Bogen |title=InYourSpeakers: Reviews: Weezer: Death to False Metal |url=http://inyourspeakers.com/content/review/weezer-death-false-metal-11102010 |date=10 November 2010 |accessdate=23 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113956/http://inyourspeakers.com/content/review/weezer-death-false-metal-11102010 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev9score = 3.5/10<ref name=Pitchfork>{{cite web |first=Ian|last=Cohen|title=Album Reviews: Weezer: Pinkerton (Deluxe Edition) / Death to False Metal|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14817-pinkerton-deluxe-edition-death-to-false-metal/|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=15 November 2010}}</ref>\n| rev10 = Punknews.org\n| rev10score = {{rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |first=Tori |last=Pederson |title=Weezer - Death to False Metal|url=https://www.punknews.org/review/9966/weezer-death-to-false-metal|website=Punknews.org|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to [[Metacritic]], ''Death to False Metal'' has received mixed reviews, receiving an average score of 56/100.<ref name=MC/>\n\n[[AllMusic]] gave the album 4 out of 5 stars, saying \"It's a wonder why a few of these cuts didn't pop up before this, but as a collection of outtakes, they hold together better than some of the band's proper albums.\"<ref name=AllMusic/> ''[[Drowned in Sound]]'' gave it a 4 out of 10, calling it \"lineage of dumbed down music to even more dumb lyrics\", citing songs such as \"Blowin' My Stack\" and \"Trampoline\".<ref name=DiN/> [[IGN]] gave it a 7.5 out of 10, citing \"...the album feels a lot more cohesive than similar rarities sets, though a little more diversity would have made for a more interesting listen.\"<ref name=IGN/>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Rivers Cuomo]], except where noted\n| total_length = 32:52\n| title1 = [[Turning Up the Radio]]\n| length1 = 3:37\n| note1 = Cuomo, Alfredo Robert Carballo, Paul Dutton, Patrick Gannon, Joshua Godinez, Daniel James Kelsch, Reshad Malik, Cameron L. Maris, Sam Mitchell, Taylor Morden, Daniel Powell, Lauren Sonder, Nishant Thakur, Justin Vail, Mike Danger, Kingsly Vanata & Ryan Wiesbrock\n| title2 = I Don't Want Your Loving\n| length2 = 3:03\n| title3 = Blowin' My Stack\n| length3 = 3:44\n| note3 = Cuomo, Brian Bell, Scott Shriner\n| title4 = Losing My Mind\n| length4 = 4:02\n| title5 = Everyone\n| length5 = 2:49\n| title6 = I'm a Robot\n| length6 = 2:31\n| title7 = Trampoline\n| length7 = 2:45\n| title8 = The Odd Couple\n| length8 = 3:07\n| title9 = Autopilot\n| length9 = 2:57\n| title10 = [[Un-Break My Heart|Unbreak My Heart]]\n| length10 = 4:11\n| note10 = [[Diane Warren]]\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = International bonus tracks\n| title11         = Yellow Camaro\n| note11          = Brian Bell\n| length11        = 1:54\n| title12         = Outta Here\n| length12        = 2:34\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline         = iTunes Store/Vinyl bonus track\n| title13          = Mykel and Carli \n| length13         = 3:13\n}}\n\n* \"Unbreak My Heart\" originally performed by [[Toni Braxton]].\n* \"Yellow Camaro\" exclusive Japanese track.\n* \"Mykel and Carli\" unreleased version from [[Weezer (1994 album)|''The Blue Album'''s]] sessions.\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n<ref>https://www.allmusic.com/album/death-to-false-metal-mw0002059085/credits</ref>\n\n'''Weezer'''\n* [[Rivers Cuomo]] \u2013 lead vocals, guitar, keyboard\n* [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]] \u2013 drums, percussion\n* [[Brian Bell]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals, synth, keyboard\n* [[Scott Shriner]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n* [[David Campbell (American arranger/composer)|David Campbell]] \u2013 [[string section|string]] [[arrangement]]s, [[conductor (music)|conducting]]\n* Taylor Morden \u2013 guitar, synthesizer, backing vocals\n\n'''Design'''\n* Andy Mueller \u2013 art direction\n* Robert Pitt \u2013 cover painting, paintings\n* Daniel Field, Karl Koch, Sean Murphy, Spike Jonze \u2013 photography\n\n{{col-2}}\n'''Production'''\n* Chad Bamford \u2013 engineer\n* Shawn Everett \u2013 engineer, mixing\n* Taylor Morden \u2013 engineer, production\n* Rich Mouser \u2013 engineer\n* Rick Rubin \u2013 engineer\n* Jim Scott \u2013 engineer\n* Dave Collins \u2013 mastering\n* Marc McClusky \u2013 mixing (tracks: 1 to 3)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the album, which is allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLC2qC-e5YikdrY8wDvnUTi6WYO1e58bqi ''Death to False Metal''] at [[YouTube]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n* {{metacritic album|death-to-false-metal}}\n* {{MusicBrainz release group|id=51c88244-97b3-4ae5-9ffa-3a4530bb6343|name=Death to False Metal}}\n\n{{Weezer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Death To False Metal}}\n[[Category:Weezer albums]]\n[[Category:2010 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:DGC Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "OfficalKevinOsmond", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonnel", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_to_False_Metal"}
{"title_page": "Zac Henderson", "text_new": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name                = \n| image               = <!-- Only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people -- see [[WP:NONFREE]]. -->\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| number              = 24\n| position            = [[Defensive back ]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1955|10|14|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Jena, Louisiana]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|04|20|1955|10|14}}\n| death_place         = [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 1\n| weight_lbs          = 190\n| high_school          = [[Nonce High School|Burkburnett (TX)]]\n| college             = [[University of Oklahoma]]\n| undraftedyear       = 1978\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] (1978\u20131979)\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] (1980)\n* [[Toronto Argonauts]] (1982\u20131983)\n| highlights          = \n* [[James P. McCaffrey Trophy]] (1982)\n* CFL All-Star (1982)\n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1977 College Football All-America Team|1977]])\n* Second-team All-American ([[1976 College Football All-America Team|1976]])\n\n| nflnew              = zachenderson/2516310\n| pfr                 = H/HendZa20\n}}\n\n'''Zachary Ryall Henderson''' (October 14, 1955 \u2013 April 20, 2020) was an American professional [[gridiron football|football]] player who played in the [[Canadian Football League]] for four years. Henderson played [[defensive back]] for the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] and [[Toronto Argonauts]] from 1978-1983. Henderson also played one season in the [[National Football League]] for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]]. He played [[college football]] at the [[University of Oklahoma]], where he was a two-time [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]]. He died in Oklahoma City on April 20, 2020.<ref>[https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2020/04/20/former-eagles-db-zac-henderson-dies-at-64/?partner=MSN]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/aa-zac-henderson-1976-77.html College Bio]\n\n{{1974 Oklahoma Sooners football navbox}}\n{{1975 Oklahoma Sooners football navbox}}\n{{1977 College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henderson, Zac}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Jena, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Sooners football players]]\n[[Category:Hamilton Tiger-Cats players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Argonauts players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:American players of Canadian football]]\n[[Category:Grey Cup champions]]\n[[Category:Canadian football defensive backs]]\n[[Category:American football defensive backs]]\n\n\n{{Canadianfootball-defensiveback-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name                = \n| image               = <!-- Only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people -- see [[WP:NONFREE]]. -->\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| number              = 24\n| position            = [[Defensive back ]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1955|10|14|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Jena, Louisiana]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|04|20|1955|10|14}}\n| death_place         = [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 1\n| weight_lbs          = 190\n| high_school          = [[Nonce High School|Burkburnett (TX)]]\n| college             = [[University of Oklahoma]]\n| undraftedyear       = 1978\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] (1978\u20131979)\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] (1980)\n* [[Toronto Argonauts]] (1982\u20131983)\n| highlights          = \n* [[James P. McCaffrey Trophy]] (1982)\n* CFL All-Star (1982)\n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1977 College Football All-America Team|1977]])\n* Second-team All-American ([[1976 College Football All-America Team|1976]])\n\n| nflnew              = zachenderson/2516310\n| pfr                 = H/HendZa20\n}}\n\n'''Zachary Ryall Henderson''' (October 14, 1955 \u2013 April 20, 2020) was an American professional [[gridiron football|football]] player who played in the [[Canadian Football League]] for four years. Henderson played [[defensive back]] for the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] and [[Toronto Argonauts]] from 1978-1983. Henderson also played one season in the [[National Football League]] for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]]. He played college football at the [[University of Oklahoma]], where he was a two-time All-American. He died in Oklahoma City on April 20, 2020.<ref>[https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2020/04/20/former-eagles-db-zac-henderson-dies-at-64/?partner=MSN]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/aa-zac-henderson-1976-77.html College Bio]\n\n{{1974 Oklahoma Sooners football navbox}}\n{{1975 Oklahoma Sooners football navbox}}\n{{1977 College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henderson, Zac}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Jena, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Sooners football players]]\n[[Category:Hamilton Tiger-Cats players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Argonauts players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:American players of Canadian football]]\n[[Category:Grey Cup champions]]\n[[Category:Canadian football defensive backs]]\n[[Category:American football defensive backs]]\n\n\n{{Canadianfootball-defensiveback-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zac_Henderson"}
{"title_page": "Kada\u0148", "text_new": "{{for|the 13th century Mongol leader|Kadan}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Kada\u0148\n| native_name             = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Town\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Kada\u0148 2016-10-16.jpg\n| image_caption           = Panorama of the town with the [[Eger River]]\n| image_flag              = Flag of Kada\u0148.svg\n| image_shield            = Coat of arms of Kada\u0148.svg\n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = Czech Republic\n| subdivision_type1       = \n| subdivision_name1       = \n| subdivision_type2       = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region|\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Chomutov District|Chomutov]]\n| subdivision_type4       = \n| subdivision_name4       = \n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Czechia\n| pushpin_relief          = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Czech Republic \n| coordinates             = {{coord|50|22|34|N|13|16|17|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n<!-- government type, leaders -->\n| leader_title            = Mayor\n| leader_name             = Ji\u0159\u00ed Kulh\u00e1nek\n<!-- established -->\n| established_title       = First mentioned\n| established_date        = 1183\n<!-- area -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 65.62\n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 300\n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2019-01-01<ref>{{cite web |title=Population of municipalities of the Czech republic|url=https://www.czso.cz/documents/10180/91917344/1300721903.pdf/ea01e710-2ae5-49f3-8792-ebb384754346?version=1.0|publisher=Czech Statistical Office|accessdate=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 18202\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 432 01\n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = \n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = [http://www.mesto-kadan.cz/ www.mesto-kadan.cz]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Kada\u0148''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8kada\u0272|-|Cs-Kadan.ogg}}; {{lang-de|Kaaden}}), is a city in the [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region]] of the [[Czech Republic]].\nThe city lies on the banks of the river [[Oh\u0159e]]. Although it is situated in an industrial part of the Czech Republic there is no major industry within the city and people usually work in offices or have to commute. There are two large power plants nearby (Tu\u0161imice and Prun\u00e9\u0159ov). Kada\u0148 is a tourist centre with highlights being the Franciscan Monastery and the historical square with late Gothic Town Hall Tower. It is also a town with the narrowest lane in the Czech Republic - Katova uli\u010dka with only 66.1&nbsp;cm.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early history until the Thirty Years' War ===\nThere are legends accrediting the beginnings of the town to [[Celt]]ic tribes. In the 1st century A.D. Germanic tribes came, but moved on in the great Germanic migration to the west. In the 6th century the country was settled by Slavs. Some talk about a castle on ''\u00daho\u0161\u0165'' hill that might have been called [[Battle of Wogastisburg|Wogastisburg]] where a battle between [[Franks]] and [[Slavic peoples|Slavs]] occurred in 631. The battle of [[Canburg]] in 805 is also often mentioned in connection with the town, but is a mistake because locality of this name (Canburg - Kanina) is in Middle Bohemia.\n\nThe first written record is, though, of the end of the 12th century - the Czech prince granted the \"market town\" of Kada\u0148 to the [[Knights of St. John]]. Slavic rulers called German settlers into the country, offering them freedom but gaining taxes at the same time. The Knights Hospitaller built the first church in Kada\u0148 - [[St. John the Baptist]] - which still stands in the part of town called Hospitaller Suburb, but is now in the [[Baroque]] style. In the 13th century, the town was promoted to a \"Royal City\". It began to thrive and a new town was built on the heights above the river, with a castle and [[Franciscan Monastery in Kada\u0148|Franciscan monastery]]. There was a big fire in 1362. However, Emperor [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles IV]] who twice visited the city (1367 and 1374) granted it several municipal rights (home rule, a vineyard, and an annual market) that made it flourish again. The reign of [[Wenceslaus IV]] (V\u00e1clav IV) produced the skilled clockmaker [[Mikul\u00e1\u0161 of Kada\u0148]] (''Mikul\u00e1\u0161 z Kadan\u011b''), who, together with mathematician and astronomer [[Jan Sindel|Jan \u0160indel]], designed the [[Prague Orloj]].\n\nThe 15th century brought a new dimension to the history of Kada\u0148: the town and castle often used to be pledged to royal creditors. At the end of the rule of [[George of Pod\u011bbrady]] first the town and later the castle was captured by [[Jan Hasi\u0161tejnsk\u00fd z Lobkovic]] (John of Lobkowicz and Hassenstein), who seemed to see Kada\u0148 as a suitable capital for his dependent territories. The establishment and construction of the monastery of the [[Franciscans]] of strict observance, built as a family burial-place and later a pardon place of [[Fourteen Holy Helpers]], may reflect his ambitions for the town. Jan Hasi\u0161tejnsk\u00fd died in 1517 and is buried in the Church of Fourteen Holy Helpers. His tomb is still on display in the Church, now part of the municipal museum. The same year saw the beginning of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] in Germany, which had an immediate impact on the atmosphere in German speaking Kada\u0148. In 1534, \"Kada\u0148 religious peace\" was negotiated here between [[W\u00fcrttemberg]] Protestants and [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor]] for the Catholic side. In the [[Thirty Years' War]] during the next century, Kada\u0148 suffered from fires and plundering by various armies on their way to the battlefields of [[Bohemia]]. After the war, the formerly Czech-German town became a monolingual German domain.\n\n=== The Age of Enlightenment until the 19th century ===\n[[File:Kadan river.jpg|thumb|right|Kada\u0148 seen from the river]]\n\nDuring the [[Silesian Wars]] Kada\u0148 was a foothold for the withdrawing French army that fortified in the Franciscan monastery and was besieged by Hungarian and Croatian units of the Austrian army. The door of the monastery church still shows the bullet holes from that battle on October 14, 1742. The town caught fire in 1746, providing a great opportunity for Kada\u0148's \"Christopher Wren\" - ''Johann Christoph Kosch''. He built many Baroque buildings, including the Church of the [[Elevation of the Holy Cross]], the Church of the Holy Family and the monastery of the [[Order of St. Elisabeth]]. The Castle of Kada\u0148 was rebuilt to serve as a barracks in the time of [[Maria Theresa of Austria]]. Her son [[Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor|Joseph II]] visited Kada\u0148 in 1779. Joseph's reforms also affected town life. The monastery of [[Minorites]] was closed and thereafter became the premises of the first Grammar School under control of the [[Piarists]] from 1803 to 1823. 1788 saw the inauguration of the town municipal council. [[Jakob Marzel Sternberger]] was its first Mayor and held office until 1822. His great-grandson [[Jacob Sternberger]] emigrated to the United States in 1850 as part of the first wave of European immigrants of that time ([[Max Kade]] Institute).\n\nThe last great fire damaged the town in 1811 and since then, the historic centre has retained its pattern. After the [[Revolution of 1848]] the letdown town became a district centre. The institute of the district town lasted in Kada\u0148 for 110 years when it was affiliated with [[Chomutov]] district. In the second half of the 19th century homeland study activities developed and a number of institutions, clubs and societies were established. The national composition of the Kada\u0148 population was very explicit - over 90% German and only 3% Czech, with a Jewish community as well.\n\n=== 20th century ===\nAt the start of the 20th century, the \"Society of Friends of the Museum in Kaaden\" decided to document the towns' history by opening a museum.\n\nIn the final weeks of [[World War I]], [[Czechoslovakia]] was established on 28 October 1918, its Bohemian, Moravian and Silesian component having been defined by the historic borders of the Czech (Bohemian) kingdom. However, most of the German border population, was not enthusiastic about becoming part of a new republic with a clearly Slavonic definition. Instead, four regional self-governed states emerged along the borderland, Kada\u0148  declared itself part of [[German Bohemia]]. On 4 March 1919, the first assembly of the Austria parliament. This was the occasion for both peaceful and violent demonstrations in the mostly German-populated border cities. In Kada\u0148, the curfew and martial law was declared and the Czechoslovak military forces were sent in. The demonstration in Kada\u0148 for [[self determination]] was the bloodiest. According to Swiss [[Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung]] report of 7 March 1919, 17 persons were killed, 30 badly wounded, and 80 wounded there. Over all, 25 victims were buried in a memorial grave at the central cemetery. It was restored after the fall of communism in 1989.\n\nAfter the [[Munich Agreement]] in later September 1938, Kaaden became part of Reichsgau [[Sudetenland]]. The local Czech people were forced to move to central Czechoslovakia, the remaining ones and the Jewish community was strongly oppressed. The synagogue was burnt down during the [[Kristallnacht]] of November 9, 1939. According to [[Bene\u0161 decrees]], after the [[Second World War]], all of the German population was transferred ([[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia during and after World War II]]), and the area was re-settled by Czech people, many without roots in this region.\n\n[[File:Prefab.jpg|thumb|left|165px|A prefabricated house after reconstruction]]\nFrom the 1950s, new prefabricated housing estates were built that reached the outer parts of the historical conurbation in the 1960s and 70s. This expansion was necessary because many people had moved in to get jobs in the region's thriving mining and electrical industries. The historical monuments were dilapidated and uncared-for. Before 1989 some parts of the historical centre were intended to be replaced by modern housing. Fortunately the [[Velvet Revolution]] changed the trend of development in the town and brought about a change in attitudes towards the cultural values of the past. The historical heart of Kada\u0148 began to be repaired and after 15 years it has become a pearl of the region. There is now a new site on the bank of the Oh\u0159e River being planned and projected- [[Maxipes F\u00edk]] Embankment with a lot of attractions both for children and adults. The town has been turning to be a tourist centre of the predominantly industrial region. The only drawback for tourism is the lack of a higher-capacity hotel in the town.\n\n== Places of interest ==\n* [[Franciscan Monastery in Kada\u0148|Franciscan Monastery]] (museum)\n* Town Hall Tower\n* The Castle\n* The Old Square\n* Holy Tower\n* Barbican\n* Lookout Tower on Svat\u00fd kope\u010dek (Holy Hill)\n\n== Galleries ==\n[[File:Galerie Kisza.jpg|thumb|80px|left|U netop\u00fdra]]\n* \n* M\u011bstsk\u00e1 galerie Josefa Lieslera (\"pod v\u011b\u017e\u00ed\" - ''under the tower'')\n* M\u011bstsk\u00e1 galerie Karla Havl\u00ed\u010dka (\"na hrad\u011b\" - ''in the castle'')\n* Galerie U Netop\u00fdra also called Kisza Gallery, is one of the largest private galleries with permanent exhibition in Central Europe\n* Galerie U Adama (Jitka Gavendov\u00e1 and Franti\u0161ek Vl\u010dek)\n* Galerie Na p\u016fd\u011b - \"on the attic\" (of the Franciscan Monastery)\n* Pictures and photographs for sale are usually in a lot of local restaurants and boarding houses\n\n== Annual events ==\n* Emperor's Day (on last August Sunday, takes place on the square with a lot of attractions)\n* [[Maxipes Fik|Maxipes F\u00edk]] Birthday\n* [[Wenceslas Pantaleon Kirwitzer|Kirwitzer]] Astronomical Day\n* Old Czech Carnival\n* Franciscan Summer\n* Vine Harvest Festival\n* ''Vysm\u00e1t\u00e9 l\u00e9to'' - Summer Rock Fest\n* Nativity Play\n* Passion of Christ Play\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:Zemedelska skola.jpg|thumb|120px|right|Agricultural School]][[File:Gymnasium in Kada\u0148.jpg|thumb|120px|left|Gymnasium]][[File:Prumyslova skola.jpg|thumb|120px|left|Industrial School]]\n\nKada\u0148 is home to several secondary schools with a long history.\nThe oldest of them is the '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' that was established in 1803 with 99 students and continued under the control of the [[Piarists]] until 1823. The seat of the old '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' was a former [[Minorites]] Monastery (different from the Franciscan Monastery) near the square in a building which is now residence of the Regional Archives. The institute of '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' was then reestablished in 1872 in a new building. The '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' was again closed in 1951 and the new Industrial School moved to the building. It is still there today. A new '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' was established in 1968 and has remained on the same premises since 1978. The Industrial School specialized at first on mining (because of the [[lignite]] and [[uranium]] mines in the surroundings), however since 1957 it has been specialized on building and finally in 2001 it added Commercial Academy to its educational program so now it is called '''Industrial Building School and Commercial Academy'''. The '''Agriculture School''' (now '''''SO\u0160S a SOU Amos''''') was established in 1862 as so-called ''Ackerbauschule''. In front of the building there are valuable statues of [[Albrecht Thaer|Albrecht Daniel Thaer]] and [[Justus von Liebig]] (restored in 2003). The teaching in all the schools was in German language until 1945. There are 4 Elementary Schools in Kada\u0148 and a school for handicapped children.\n\n==Notable people==\n===History===\n* [[Peter Georg Niger]] (Schwartz) (1434 - 1481 or 1484) - theologian\n* [[Jan Hasi\u0161tejnsk\u00fd z Lobkovic]] (1450 - 1517) - traveller, politician and writer\n* Petr \u0160t\u011brba ze \u0160t\u011brbic (1517/18-1591) - scriber and translator\n* Jan Sandel - translator from German ([[Wenceslaus H\u00e1jek]]'s ''[[Bohemian Chronicle]]'', 1543)\n* [[Wenceslas Pantaleon Kirwitzer|Wenceslas (V\u00e1clav) Pantaleon Kirwitzer]] (1588 - 1626 [[Macau]]) - astronomer\n* [[Wilhelm Nigrinus]] (Schwartz) (1588 - 1638) ([[:de:Wilhelm Nigrinus]]), [[ethnologist]]\n* [[Theodor Innitzer]] (1875 - 1955) - [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]], [[Archbishop of Vienna]]\n* [[Hans Zeisel]] (1905 - 1992 [[Chicago]]), sociologist and economist\n* [[Petr Kl\u00edma]] (1964 born to Kada\u0148 parents in [[Chomutov]] hospital), ice hockey player, [[Stanley Cup]] winner (1990, [[Edmonton Oilers]])\n\n===Music===\n* [[Edward Goll]] (1884 - 1949, [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]), pianist and music teacher\n\n===Art===\n[[File:Liesler.jpg|thumb|150px|A Picture by J. Liesler]]\n* [[Karel Havl\u00ed\u010dek painter|Karel Havl\u00ed\u010dek]] (1907 - 1988)\n* [[Josef Liesler]] (1912 Vidolice u Kadan\u011b - August 6, 2005 Prague)\n* Josef Koke\u0161 (1906 - 1967)\n* Rudolf Koblic (1933 - 2003)\n* Herbert Kisza (*1943)\n* Vojt\u011bch Kraus\n* Franti\u0161ek Vl\u010dek (*1947)\n* Jitka Gavendov\u00e1 (*1946)\n* Jitka K\u0159ivancov\u00e1\n* Pavel Wolf\n* Dalibor Vajnar\n* Kry\u0161tof Kisza\n* Margo Paran (*1946) - an [[Israel]] artist and poet born in Kada\u0148\n* [[Josef Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]]\n\n===Sport===\n* [[Aneta L\u00e9dlov\u00e1]] -Woman Hockey player with Czech National team, Robert Morris University (USA)\n* [[Ond\u0159ej Ka\u0161e]] - Professional Ice Hockey Player for the Boston Bruins\n\n===Literature===\n* [[V\u00e1clav \u0158ez\u00e1\u010d]]\n* [[Rudolf \u010cechura]]\n\n==Churches==\nThere are churches and chapels of four Christian denominations: [[Roman Catholic Church]], [[Czechoslovak Hussite Church]], [[Evangelical Church of Czech Brethren]] and [[Orthodox Church]]. Roman Catholic Parish Church of the Elevation of the Holy Cross is situated in the square.\n\n==Parks and urban vegetation==\n[[File:Smetanovy sady.jpg|thumb|left| [[Bed\u0159ich Smetana|Smetana]] Park]]\n\nKada\u0148 is situated at the edges of [[Doupovsk\u00e9 hory|Doupov Mountains]] with mixed forests and [[Ore Mountains (Central Europe)|Ore Mountains]] with coniferous stand. There were three major parks in the 19th century enlarging town. The Municipal park - now ''Smetanovy sady'' - was founded by a Kada\u0148 inhabitant and future Mayor Peter Prinzl in 1852. Landscape park was also established on the rocks over the Oh\u0159e river next to the Franciscan monastery. A new organisation ''Anpflanzungs- und Versch\u00f6nerungsverein Kaaden'' concentrated its energy on park layout for so-called ''Svat\u00e1 hora'' or ''Svat\u00fd kope\u010dek'' - ''Holy Hill'' that was called \"holy\" (''heiliger berg'' since 1541) for its position above the ''holy'' pilgrimage monastery. The hill with abandoned rock vineyards became an English park with a lot of viewpoints, arbours and benches at the turn of the 20th century. [[Jaroslav Havl\u00ed\u010dek]] wrote in his novel ''\"Vl\u010d\u00ed k\u016f\u017ee\"'' about Svat\u00e1 hora that it was a place for romantic walks of young couples. The park the area around was also referred to as ''Sommerfrische Kaaden'' - Kada\u0148 summer resort. It was, however, not cared for in the times of World War II and Communists after 1948 left the park to be completely devastated and overgrown. However, the socialist planners projected the new residential areas with a lot of greenery inside. A new large park came to existence on the other side of the town on the left bank of Byst\u0159ice stream - now ''Rooseveltovy sady''.\n\n==Interesting facts==\n* A Swiss-French writer [[Benjamin Constant]] set a part of his famous novel [[Adolphe]] (1816) in Kada\u0148, referring to it as ''Caden, petite ville de la Boh\u00eame''. [http://www.badosa.com/bin/obra.pl?id=n081-06]\n* V\u00e1clav Vanya from Kada\u0148 [[\u0160vejk]] Restaurant ''U V\u011b\u017ei\u010dky'' won the national [[Pilsner Urquell]] Master Bartender competition 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nejlep\u0161\u00edm v\u00fd\u010depn\u00edm v \u010cesk\u00e9 republice je V\u00e1clav Vanya z kada\u0148sk\u00e9ho \u0160vejk restaurantu U V\u011b\u017ei\u010dky|url=http://www.homebrewing.cz/clanek/3431/Nejlepsim-vycepnim-v-Ceske-republice-je-Vaclav-Vanya-z-kadanskeho-Svejk-restaurantu-U-vezicky.htm}}</ref>\n* There is a [[dive bar]] named Kada\u0148 located in [[San Diego]], [[California]]. [http://www.kadanclub.com/]\n\n==Environs and tips to visit==\n* [[Hasi\u0161tejn]] Castle\n* \u00daho\u0161\u0165 hill\n* [[Kl\u00e1\u0161terec nad Oh\u0159\u00ed]]\n* [[Kr\u00e1sn\u00fd Dv\u016fr]]\n* ZOOpark [[Chomutov]]\n* [[Nechranice]] reservoir\n* Egerberk Castle\n* \u0160umburk Castle\n* [[Hauen\u0161tejn|Hauen\u0161tejn Castle]] / Horn\u00ed Hrad\n* [[Karlovy Vary]] - 44&nbsp;km\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the Czech Republic}}\n\nKada\u0148 is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web|title=Ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed str\u00e1nky m\u011bsta Kadan\u011b|url=http://www.mesto-kadan.cz/|publisher=M\u011bsto Kada\u0148|language=cs|accessdate=2019-08-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614111241/http://www.mesto-kadan.cz/|archive-date=2012-06-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Aue]], [[Germany]]\n*{{flagicon|BEL}} [[Halle, Belgium]]\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Vara Municipality|Vara]], [[Sweden]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Kada\u0148}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120614111241/http://www.mesto-kadan.cz/ Municipal website]\n* [http://www.muzeumkadan.cz/ Municipal Museum]\n* [http://www.gymnazium-kadan.cz/ Gymnasium]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180805045159/http://galerieuadama.cz/ Galerie U Adama]\n\n{{Chomutov District}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kadan}}\n[[Category:Kada\u0148|*]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Chomutov District]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Czech Republic]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 13th century Mongol leader|Kadan}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Kada\u0148\n| native_name             = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Town\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Kada\u0148 2016-10-16.jpg\n| image_caption           = Panorama of the town with the [[Eger River]]\n| image_flag              = Flag of Kada\u0148.svg\n| image_shield            = KadanZnak.gif\n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = Czech Republic\n| subdivision_type1       = \n| subdivision_name1       = \n| subdivision_type2       = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region|\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Chomutov District|Chomutov]]\n| subdivision_type4       = \n| subdivision_name4       = \n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Czechia\n| pushpin_relief          = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Czech Republic \n| coordinates             = {{coord|50|22|34|N|13|16|17|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n<!-- government type, leaders -->\n| leader_title            = Mayor\n| leader_name             = Ji\u0159\u00ed Kulh\u00e1nek\n<!-- established -->\n| established_title       = First mentioned\n| established_date        = 1183\n<!-- area -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 65.62\n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 300\n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2019-01-01<ref>{{cite web |title=Population of municipalities of the Czech republic|url=https://www.czso.cz/documents/10180/91917344/1300721903.pdf/ea01e710-2ae5-49f3-8792-ebb384754346?version=1.0|publisher=Czech Statistical Office|accessdate=2019-04-30}}</ref>\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 18202\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 432 01\n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = \n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = [http://www.mesto-kadan.cz/ www.mesto-kadan.cz]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Kada\u0148''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8kada\u0272|-|Cs-Kadan.ogg}}; {{lang-de|Kaaden}}), is a city in the [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region]] of the [[Czech Republic]].\nThe city lies on the banks of the river [[Oh\u0159e]]. Although it is situated in an industrial part of the Czech Republic there is no major industry within the city and people usually work in offices or have to commute. There are two large power plants nearby (Tu\u0161imice and Prun\u00e9\u0159ov). Kada\u0148 is a tourist centre with highlights being the Franciscan Monastery and the historical square with late Gothic Town Hall Tower. It is also a town with the narrowest lane in the Czech Republic - Katova uli\u010dka with only 66.1&nbsp;cm.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early history until the Thirty Years' War ===\nThere are legends accrediting the beginnings of the town to [[Celt]]ic tribes. In the 1st century A.D. Germanic tribes came, but moved on in the great Germanic migration to the west. In the 6th century the country was settled by Slavs. Some talk about a castle on ''\u00daho\u0161\u0165'' hill that might have been called [[Battle of Wogastisburg|Wogastisburg]] where a battle between [[Franks]] and [[Slavic peoples|Slavs]] occurred in 631. The battle of [[Canburg]] in 805 is also often mentioned in connection with the town, but is a mistake because locality of this name (Canburg - Kanina) is in Middle Bohemia.\n\nThe first written record is, though, of the end of the 12th century - the Czech prince granted the \"market town\" of Kada\u0148 to the [[Knights of St. John]]. Slavic rulers called German settlers into the country, offering them freedom but gaining taxes at the same time. The Knights Hospitaller built the first church in Kada\u0148 - [[St. John the Baptist]] - which still stands in the part of town called Hospitaller Suburb, but is now in the [[Baroque]] style. In the 13th century, the town was promoted to a \"Royal City\". It began to thrive and a new town was built on the heights above the river, with a castle and [[Franciscan Monastery in Kada\u0148|Franciscan monastery]]. There was a big fire in 1362. However, Emperor [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles IV]] who twice visited the city (1367 and 1374) granted it several municipal rights (home rule, a vineyard, and an annual market) that made it flourish again. The reign of [[Wenceslaus IV]] (V\u00e1clav IV) produced the skilled clockmaker [[Mikul\u00e1\u0161 of Kada\u0148]] (''Mikul\u00e1\u0161 z Kadan\u011b''), who, together with mathematician and astronomer [[Jan Sindel|Jan \u0160indel]], designed the [[Prague Orloj]].\n\nThe 15th century brought a new dimension to the history of Kada\u0148: the town and castle often used to be pledged to royal creditors. At the end of the rule of [[George of Pod\u011bbrady]] first the town and later the castle was captured by [[Jan Hasi\u0161tejnsk\u00fd z Lobkovic]] (John of Lobkowicz and Hassenstein), who seemed to see Kada\u0148 as a suitable capital for his dependent territories. The establishment and construction of the monastery of the [[Franciscans]] of strict observance, built as a family burial-place and later a pardon place of [[Fourteen Holy Helpers]], may reflect his ambitions for the town. Jan Hasi\u0161tejnsk\u00fd died in 1517 and is buried in the Church of Fourteen Holy Helpers. His tomb is still on display in the Church, now part of the municipal museum. The same year saw the beginning of the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] in Germany, which had an immediate impact on the atmosphere in German speaking Kada\u0148. In 1534, \"Kada\u0148 religious peace\" was negotiated here between [[W\u00fcrttemberg]] Protestants and [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor]] for the Catholic side. In the [[Thirty Years' War]] during the next century, Kada\u0148 suffered from fires and plundering by various armies on their way to the battlefields of [[Bohemia]]. After the war, the formerly Czech-German town became a monolingual German domain.\n\n=== The Age of Enlightenment until the 19th century ===\n[[File:Kadan river.jpg|thumb|right|Kada\u0148 seen from the river]]\n\nDuring the [[Silesian Wars]] Kada\u0148 was a foothold for the withdrawing French army that fortified in the Franciscan monastery and was besieged by Hungarian and Croatian units of the Austrian army. The door of the monastery church still shows the bullet holes from that battle on October 14, 1742. The town caught fire in 1746, providing a great opportunity for Kada\u0148's \"Christopher Wren\" - ''Johann Christoph Kosch''. He built many Baroque buildings, including the Church of the [[Elevation of the Holy Cross]], the Church of the Holy Family and the monastery of the [[Order of St. Elisabeth]]. The Castle of Kada\u0148 was rebuilt to serve as a barracks in the time of [[Maria Theresa of Austria]]. Her son [[Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor|Joseph II]] visited Kada\u0148 in 1779. Joseph's reforms also affected town life. The monastery of [[Minorites]] was closed and thereafter became the premises of the first Grammar School under control of the [[Piarists]] from 1803 to 1823. 1788 saw the inauguration of the town municipal council. [[Jakob Marzel Sternberger]] was its first Mayor and held office until 1822. His great-grandson [[Jacob Sternberger]] emigrated to the United States in 1850 as part of the first wave of European immigrants of that time ([[Max Kade]] Institute).\n\nThe last great fire damaged the town in 1811 and since then, the historic centre has retained its pattern. After the [[Revolution of 1848]] the letdown town became a district centre. The institute of the district town lasted in Kada\u0148 for 110 years when it was affiliated with [[Chomutov]] district. In the second half of the 19th century homeland study activities developed and a number of institutions, clubs and societies were established. The national composition of the Kada\u0148 population was very explicit - over 90% German and only 3% Czech, with a Jewish community as well.\n\n=== 20th century ===\nAt the start of the 20th century, the \"Society of Friends of the Museum in Kaaden\" decided to document the towns' history by opening a museum.\n\nIn the final weeks of [[World War I]], [[Czechoslovakia]] was established on 28 October 1918, its Bohemian, Moravian and Silesian component having been defined by the historic borders of the Czech (Bohemian) kingdom. However, most of the German border population, was not enthusiastic about becoming part of a new republic with a clearly Slavonic definition. Instead, four regional self-governed states emerged along the borderland, Kada\u0148  declared itself part of [[German Bohemia]]. On 4 March 1919, the first assembly of the Austria parliament. This was the occasion for both peaceful and violent demonstrations in the mostly German-populated border cities. In Kada\u0148, the curfew and martial law was declared and the Czechoslovak military forces were sent in. The demonstration in Kada\u0148 for [[self determination]] was the bloodiest. According to Swiss [[Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung]] report of 7 March 1919, 17 persons were killed, 30 badly wounded, and 80 wounded there. Over all, 25 victims were buried in a memorial grave at the central cemetery. It was restored after the fall of communism in 1989.\n\nAfter the [[Munich Agreement]] in later September 1938, Kaaden became part of Reichsgau [[Sudetenland]]. The local Czech people were forced to move to central Czechoslovakia, the remaining ones and the Jewish community was strongly oppressed. The synagogue was burnt down during the [[Kristallnacht]] of November 9, 1939. According to [[Bene\u0161 decrees]], after the [[Second World War]], all of the German population was transferred ([[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia during and after World War II]]), and the area was re-settled by Czech people, many without roots in this region.\n\n[[File:Prefab.jpg|thumb|left|165px|A prefabricated house after reconstruction]]\nFrom the 1950s, new prefabricated housing estates were built that reached the outer parts of the historical conurbation in the 1960s and 70s. This expansion was necessary because many people had moved in to get jobs in the region's thriving mining and electrical industries. The historical monuments were dilapidated and uncared-for. Before 1989 some parts of the historical centre were intended to be replaced by modern housing. Fortunately the [[Velvet Revolution]] changed the trend of development in the town and brought about a change in attitudes towards the cultural values of the past. The historical heart of Kada\u0148 began to be repaired and after 15 years it has become a pearl of the region. There is now a new site on the bank of the Oh\u0159e River being planned and projected- [[Maxipes F\u00edk]] Embankment with a lot of attractions both for children and adults. The town has been turning to be a tourist centre of the predominantly industrial region. The only drawback for tourism is the lack of a higher-capacity hotel in the town.\n\n== Places of interest ==\n* [[Franciscan Monastery in Kada\u0148|Franciscan Monastery]] (museum)\n* Town Hall Tower\n* The Castle\n* The Old Square\n* Holy Tower\n* Barbican\n* Lookout Tower on Svat\u00fd kope\u010dek (Holy Hill)\n\n== Galleries ==\n[[File:Galerie Kisza.jpg|thumb|80px|left|U netop\u00fdra]]\n* \n* M\u011bstsk\u00e1 galerie Josefa Lieslera (\"pod v\u011b\u017e\u00ed\" - ''under the tower'')\n* M\u011bstsk\u00e1 galerie Karla Havl\u00ed\u010dka (\"na hrad\u011b\" - ''in the castle'')\n* Galerie U Netop\u00fdra also called Kisza Gallery, is one of the largest private galleries with permanent exhibition in Central Europe\n* Galerie U Adama (Jitka Gavendov\u00e1 and Franti\u0161ek Vl\u010dek)\n* Galerie Na p\u016fd\u011b - \"on the attic\" (of the Franciscan Monastery)\n* Pictures and photographs for sale are usually in a lot of local restaurants and boarding houses\n\n== Annual events ==\n* Emperor's Day (on last August Sunday, takes place on the square with a lot of attractions)\n* [[Maxipes Fik|Maxipes F\u00edk]] Birthday\n* [[Wenceslas Pantaleon Kirwitzer|Kirwitzer]] Astronomical Day\n* Old Czech Carnival\n* Franciscan Summer\n* Vine Harvest Festival\n* ''Vysm\u00e1t\u00e9 l\u00e9to'' - Summer Rock Fest\n* Nativity Play\n* Passion of Christ Play\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:Zemedelska skola.jpg|thumb|120px|right|Agricultural School]][[File:Gymnasium in Kada\u0148.jpg|thumb|120px|left|Gymnasium]][[File:Prumyslova skola.jpg|thumb|120px|left|Industrial School]]\n\nKada\u0148 is home to several secondary schools with a long history.\nThe oldest of them is the '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' that was established in 1803 with 99 students and continued under the control of the [[Piarists]] until 1823. The seat of the old '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' was a former [[Minorites]] Monastery (different from the Franciscan Monastery) near the square in a building which is now residence of the Regional Archives. The institute of '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' was then reestablished in 1872 in a new building. The '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' was again closed in 1951 and the new Industrial School moved to the building. It is still there today. A new '''[[Gymnasium Kada\u0148|Gymnasium]]''' was established in 1968 and has remained on the same premises since 1978. The Industrial School specialized at first on mining (because of the [[lignite]] and [[uranium]] mines in the surroundings), however since 1957 it has been specialized on building and finally in 2001 it added Commercial Academy to its educational program so now it is called '''Industrial Building School and Commercial Academy'''. The '''Agriculture School''' (now '''''SO\u0160S a SOU Amos''''') was established in 1862 as so-called ''Ackerbauschule''. In front of the building there are valuable statues of [[Albrecht Thaer|Albrecht Daniel Thaer]] and [[Justus von Liebig]] (restored in 2003). The teaching in all the schools was in German language until 1945. There are 4 Elementary Schools in Kada\u0148 and a school for handicapped children.\n\n==Notable people==\n===History===\n* [[Peter Georg Niger]] (Schwartz) (1434 - 1481 or 1484) - theologian\n* [[Jan Hasi\u0161tejnsk\u00fd z Lobkovic]] (1450 - 1517) - traveller, politician and writer\n* Petr \u0160t\u011brba ze \u0160t\u011brbic (1517/18-1591) - scriber and translator\n* Jan Sandel - translator from German ([[Wenceslaus H\u00e1jek]]'s ''[[Bohemian Chronicle]]'', 1543)\n* [[Wenceslas Pantaleon Kirwitzer|Wenceslas (V\u00e1clav) Pantaleon Kirwitzer]] (1588 - 1626 [[Macau]]) - astronomer\n* [[Wilhelm Nigrinus]] (Schwartz) (1588 - 1638) ([[:de:Wilhelm Nigrinus]]), [[ethnologist]]\n* [[Theodor Innitzer]] (1875 - 1955) - [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]], [[Archbishop of Vienna]]\n* [[Hans Zeisel]] (1905 - 1992 [[Chicago]]), sociologist and economist\n* [[Petr Kl\u00edma]] (1964 born to Kada\u0148 parents in [[Chomutov]] hospital), ice hockey player, [[Stanley Cup]] winner (1990, [[Edmonton Oilers]])\n\n===Music===\n* [[Edward Goll]] (1884 - 1949, [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]), pianist and music teacher\n\n===Art===\n[[File:Liesler.jpg|thumb|150px|A Picture by J. Liesler]]\n* [[Karel Havl\u00ed\u010dek painter|Karel Havl\u00ed\u010dek]] (1907 - 1988)\n* [[Josef Liesler]] (1912 Vidolice u Kadan\u011b - August 6, 2005 Prague)\n* Josef Koke\u0161 (1906 - 1967)\n* Rudolf Koblic (1933 - 2003)\n* Herbert Kisza (*1943)\n* Vojt\u011bch Kraus\n* Franti\u0161ek Vl\u010dek (*1947)\n* Jitka Gavendov\u00e1 (*1946)\n* Jitka K\u0159ivancov\u00e1\n* Pavel Wolf\n* Dalibor Vajnar\n* Kry\u0161tof Kisza\n* Margo Paran (*1946) - an [[Israel]] artist and poet born in Kada\u0148\n* [[Josef Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]]\n\n===Sport===\n* [[Aneta L\u00e9dlov\u00e1]] -Woman Hockey player with Czech National team, Robert Morris University (USA)\n* [[Ond\u0159ej Ka\u0161e]] - Professional Ice Hockey Player for the Boston Bruins\n\n===Literature===\n* [[V\u00e1clav \u0158ez\u00e1\u010d]]\n* [[Rudolf \u010cechura]]\n\n==Churches==\nThere are churches and chapels of four Christian denominations: [[Roman Catholic Church]], [[Czechoslovak Hussite Church]], [[Evangelical Church of Czech Brethren]] and [[Orthodox Church]]. Roman Catholic Parish Church of the Elevation of the Holy Cross is situated in the square.\n\n==Parks and urban vegetation==\n[[File:Smetanovy sady.jpg|thumb|left| [[Bed\u0159ich Smetana|Smetana]] Park]]\n\nKada\u0148 is situated at the edges of [[Doupovsk\u00e9 hory|Doupov Mountains]] with mixed forests and [[Ore Mountains (Central Europe)|Ore Mountains]] with coniferous stand. There were three major parks in the 19th century enlarging town. The Municipal park - now ''Smetanovy sady'' - was founded by a Kada\u0148 inhabitant and future Mayor Peter Prinzl in 1852. Landscape park was also established on the rocks over the Oh\u0159e river next to the Franciscan monastery. A new organisation ''Anpflanzungs- und Versch\u00f6nerungsverein Kaaden'' concentrated its energy on park layout for so-called ''Svat\u00e1 hora'' or ''Svat\u00fd kope\u010dek'' - ''Holy Hill'' that was called \"holy\" (''heiliger berg'' since 1541) for its position above the ''holy'' pilgrimage monastery. The hill with abandoned rock vineyards became an English park with a lot of viewpoints, arbours and benches at the turn of the 20th century. [[Jaroslav Havl\u00ed\u010dek]] wrote in his novel ''\"Vl\u010d\u00ed k\u016f\u017ee\"'' about Svat\u00e1 hora that it was a place for romantic walks of young couples. The park the area around was also referred to as ''Sommerfrische Kaaden'' - Kada\u0148 summer resort. It was, however, not cared for in the times of World War II and Communists after 1948 left the park to be completely devastated and overgrown. However, the socialist planners projected the new residential areas with a lot of greenery inside. A new large park came to existence on the other side of the town on the left bank of Byst\u0159ice stream - now ''Rooseveltovy sady''.\n\n==Interesting facts==\n* A Swiss-French writer [[Benjamin Constant]] set a part of his famous novel [[Adolphe]] (1816) in Kada\u0148, referring to it as ''Caden, petite ville de la Boh\u00eame''. [http://www.badosa.com/bin/obra.pl?id=n081-06]\n* V\u00e1clav Vanya from Kada\u0148 [[\u0160vejk]] Restaurant ''U V\u011b\u017ei\u010dky'' won the national [[Pilsner Urquell]] Master Bartender competition 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nejlep\u0161\u00edm v\u00fd\u010depn\u00edm v \u010cesk\u00e9 republice je V\u00e1clav Vanya z kada\u0148sk\u00e9ho \u0160vejk restaurantu U V\u011b\u017ei\u010dky|url=http://www.homebrewing.cz/clanek/3431/Nejlepsim-vycepnim-v-Ceske-republice-je-Vaclav-Vanya-z-kadanskeho-Svejk-restaurantu-U-vezicky.htm}}</ref>\n* There is a [[dive bar]] named Kada\u0148 located in [[San Diego]], [[California]]. [http://www.kadanclub.com/]\n\n==Environs and tips to visit==\n* [[Hasi\u0161tejn]] Castle\n* \u00daho\u0161\u0165 hill\n* [[Kl\u00e1\u0161terec nad Oh\u0159\u00ed]]\n* [[Kr\u00e1sn\u00fd Dv\u016fr]]\n* ZOOpark [[Chomutov]]\n* [[Nechranice]] reservoir\n* Egerberk Castle\n* \u0160umburk Castle\n* [[Hauen\u0161tejn|Hauen\u0161tejn Castle]] / Horn\u00ed Hrad\n* [[Karlovy Vary]] - 44&nbsp;km\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the Czech Republic}}\n\nKada\u0148 is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web|title=Ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed str\u00e1nky m\u011bsta Kadan\u011b|url=http://www.mesto-kadan.cz/|publisher=M\u011bsto Kada\u0148|language=cs|accessdate=2019-08-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614111241/http://www.mesto-kadan.cz/|archive-date=2012-06-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Aue]], [[Germany]]\n*{{flagicon|BEL}} [[Halle, Belgium]]\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Vara Municipality|Vara]], [[Sweden]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Kada\u0148}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120614111241/http://www.mesto-kadan.cz/ Municipal website]\n* [http://www.muzeumkadan.cz/ Municipal Museum]\n* [http://www.gymnazium-kadan.cz/ Gymnasium]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180805045159/http://galerieuadama.cz/ Galerie U Adama]\n\n{{Chomutov District}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kadan}}\n[[Category:Kada\u0148|*]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Chomutov District]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Czech Republic]]\n", "name_user": "Janbery", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(svg coa)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kada%C5%88"}
{"title_page": "Chen Shih-chung", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Chen (surname)|Chen]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Chen Shih-chung\n|native_name  = \u9673\u6642\u4e2d\n|image        = \u885b\u751f\u798f\u5229\u90e8\u90e8\u9577\u9673\u6642\u4e2d.jpg\n|caption      = \n|order1       = \n|office1      = Minister of [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (Taiwan)|Health and Welfare]] of the [[Republic of China]]\n|deputy1      = [[Ho Chi-kung]], [[Lu Pau-ching]]<br>[[Ho Chi-kung]], [[Su Li-chiung]]\n|1blankname1  = Vice\n|1namedata1   = [[Tsai Sen-tien]]<br>[[Hsueh Jui-yuan]]\n|term_start1  = 8 February 2017\n|term_end1    = \n|predecessor1 = [[Lin Tzou-yien]]\n|successor1   = \n|order2       = \n|office2      = Deputy Minister of [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (Taiwan)|Department of Health]] of the [[Republic of China]]\n|minister2    = [[Hou Sheng-mao]]\n|term_start2  = 2005\n|term_end2    = 2008\n|predecessor2 =\n|successor2   = \n|birth_date   = December 1953\n|birth_place  = \n|nationality  = [[Republic of China]]\n|party        = {{Dpp}}\n|alma_mater   = [[Taipei Medical College]]\n|signature    = \n}}\n\n'''Chen Shih-chung''' ({{zh|c=\u9673\u6642\u4e2d|p=Ch\u00e9n Sh\u00edzh\u014dng}}; born December 1953) is a Taiwanese politician. He is the current Minister of [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (Taiwan)|Health and Welfare]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2017/02/04/2003664301|first1=Fang-ho|last1=Su|first2=Chih-hsiung|last2=Chiang|first3=Hsin-fang|last3=Lee|date=4 February 2017|title=Cabinet reshuffle sees four new names|publisher=Taipei Times|accessdate=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nChen graduated from the School of Dentistry of [[Taipei Medical College]] in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mohw.gov.tw/EN/Ministry/DM2_P.aspx?f_list_no=505&fod_list_no=0&doc_no=59677&rn=321650522|date=8 February 2017|title=CHEN Shih-chung, Minister of Health and Welfare|website=Ministry of Health and Welfare|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Ministry of Health and Welfare==\nAt a press conference after being sworn-in as the health and welfare minister, Chen said that he would continue the current policy of the ministry and would try to avoid big personnel changes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2017/02/09/2003664645|first=I-chia|last=Lee|title=Health minister vows to stay the course|date=9 February 2017|publisher=Taipei Times|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 World Health Assembly===\nChen flew to [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]] and arrived on 20 May 2017 despite the absence of invitation for Taiwan to attend the [[World Health Assembly]] in 2017. The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Taiwan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] made the arrangement for Chen to attend bilateral meetings outside the assembly including other events, such as press conference, interviews and Taiwan Night held by [[non-governmental organization]].<ref>http://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3169404</ref>\n\n===2020 Covid-19 crisis===\nChen has become widely recognised in Taiwan as the main speaker at daily press conferences given by the Taiwan Centre for Disease Control (CDC). His approval rating in a poll released on 26 March 2020 was 91%.<ref>https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3906279</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n{{Executive Yuan Officials|state=collapsed}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chen, Shih-chung}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Taipei Medical University alumni]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese Ministers of Health and Welfare]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese dentists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Taiwanese politicians]]\n\n\n{{Taiwan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese name|[[Chen (surname)|Chen]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Chen Shih-chung\n|native_name  = \u9673\u6642\u4e2d\n|image        = \u885b\u751f\u798f\u5229\u90e8\u90e8\u9577\u9673\u6642\u4e2d.jpg\n|caption      = \n|order1       = \n|office1      = Minister of [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (Taiwan)|Health and Welfare]] of the [[Republic of China]]\n|deputy1      = [[Ho Chi-kung]], [[Lu Pau-ching]]<br>[[Ho Chi-kung]], [[Su Li-chiung]]\n|1blankname1  = Vice\n|1namedata1   = [[Tsai Sen-tien]]<br>[[Hsueh Jui-yuan]]\n|term_start1  = 8 February 2017\n|term_end1    = \n|predecessor1 = [[Lin Tzou-yien]]\n|successor1   = \n|order2       = \n|office2      = Deputy Minister of [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (Taiwan)|Department of Health]] of the [[Republic of China]]\n|minister2    = [[Hou Sheng-mao]]\n|term_start2  = 2005\n|term_end2    = 2008\n|predecessor2 =\n|successor2   = \n|birth_date   = December 1953\n|birth_place  = \n|nationality  = [[Republic of China]]\n|party        = {{Dpp}}\n|alma_mater   = [[Taipei Medical College]]\n|signature    = \n}}\n\n'''Chen Shih-chung''' ({{zh|c=\u9673\u6642\u4e2d|p=Ch\u00e9n Sh\u00edzh\u014dng}}; born December 1953) is a Taiwanese politician. He is the current Minister of [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (Taiwan)|Health and Welfare]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2017/02/04/2003664301|first1=Fang-ho|last1=Su|first2=Chih-hsiung|last2=Chiang|first3=Hsin-fang|last3=Lee|date=4 February 2017|title=Cabinet reshuffle sees four new names|publisher=Taipei Times|accessdate=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nChen graduated from the School of Dentistry of [[Taipei Medical College]] in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mohw.gov.tw/EN/Ministry/DM2_P.aspx?f_list_no=505&fod_list_no=0&doc_no=59677&rn=321650522|date=8 February 2017|title=CHEN Shih-chung, Minister of Health and Welfare|website=Ministry of Health and Welfare|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Ministry of Health and Welfare==\nAt a press conference after being sworn-in as the health and welfare minister, Chen said that he would continue the current policy of the ministry and would try to avoid big personnel changes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2017/02/09/2003664645|first=I-chia|last=Lee|title=Health minister vows to stay the course|date=9 February 2017|publisher=Taipei Times|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 World Health Assembly===\nChen flew to [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]] and arrived on 20 May 2017 despite the absence of invitation for Taiwan to attend the [[World Health Assembly]] in 2017. The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Taiwan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] made the arrangement for Chen to attend bilateral meetings outside the assembly including other events, such as press conference, interviews and Taiwan Night held by [[non-governmental organization]].<ref>http://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3169404</ref>\n\n===2020 Covid-19 crisis===\nChen has become widely recognised in Taiwan as the main speaker at daily press conferences given by the Taiwan Centre for Disease Control (CDC). His approval rating in a poll released on March 26, 2020 was 91%.<ref>https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3906279</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n{{Executive Yuan Officials|state=collapsed}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chen, Shih-chung}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Taipei Medical University alumni]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese Ministers of Health and Welfare]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese dentists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Taiwanese politicians]]\n\n{{Taiwan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chen_Shih-chung"}
{"title_page": "Association of Field Ornithologists", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization \n| name = Association of Field Ornithologists \n| bgcolor = black \n| fgcolor = white \n| image =Association_of_Field_Ornithologists_Logo.jpg \n| image_border = \n| size = <!-- default 200px --> \n| alt = circle with words Association of Field Ornithologists around the top and date 1922 at bottom with outline map of North and South America in the center with bird flying in the foreground\n| caption = \n| abbreviation  = AFO \n| motto = \n| predecessor = Northeastern Bird-Banding Association \n| successor = \n| formation = {{Start date|1922}} \n| type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] \n| status = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc --> \n| purpose = Ornithology \n| headquarters  = \n| location = \n| coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template --> \n| region_served = [[Americas]] \n| membership = \n| language = English, Espa\u00f1ol, Portugu\u00eas \n| general = <!-- Secretary General --> \n| leader_title  = <!-- position title for the leader of the org --> \n| leader_name   = <!-- name of leader --> \n| leader_title2 = \n| leader_name2  = \n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3  = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4  = \n| key_people = \n| main_organ  = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc --> \n| parent_organization = <!-- if one --> \n| affiliations  = <!-- if any --> \n| budget = \n| num_staff = \n| num_volunteers = \n| website = {{url|www.afonet.org}} \n| remarks = \n| former name = \n}}\n\nThe '''Association of Field Ornithologists''' (AFO) is an [[Americas|American]] [[ornithology|ornithological]] society, with a strong focus on field studies and [[bird ringing|banding]], priding itself as serving as a bridge between professional and amateur ornithologists.  It was founded in 1922 as the New England Bird Banding Association, then becoming the Northeastern Bird-Banding Association, before expanding its geographical scope and acquiring its current name.  It publishes a twice-yearly newsletter, ''AFO Afield'', as well as the quarterly '''''Journal of Field Ornithology'''''.  The AFO is a member of the [[Ornithological Council]].\n\n==Awards==\n===Skutch Award===\nOfficially named ''The Pamela and Alexander F. Skutch Research Award'', the Skutch Award of up to US$10,000 is presented annually. Applications may be made in English, Spanish or Portuguese by 15 July for the following year.  Preference is given to those who propose field research from a [[Neotropical realm|Neotropical]] base.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pamela and Alexander F. Skutch Research Award |publisher=Association of Field Ornithologists |url=http://www.afonet.org/grants/Skutch/Skutch.html |accessdate=17 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829055928/http://www.afonet.org/grants/Skutch/Skutch.html |archivedate=29 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe Skutch Award is named for [[Alexander Skutch]].\n\n===Bergstrom Award===\nThe Bergstrom Research Award is presented annually in honor of [[E. Alexander Bergstrom]].\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of ornithology awards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090222223158/http://www.afonet.org/index_english.html Association of Field Ornithologists]\n\n[[Category:Ornithological organizations]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{ornithology-org-stub}}\n{{US-org-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization \n| name = Association of Field Ornithologists \n| bgcolor = black \n| fgcolor = white \n| image =Association_of_Field_Ornithologists_Logo.jpg \n| image_border = \n| size = <!-- default 200px --> \n| alt = circle with words Association of Field Ornithologists around the top and date 1922 at bottom with outline map of North and South America in the center with bird flying in the foreground\n| caption = \n| abbreviation  = AFO \n| motto = \n| predecessor = Northeastern Bird-Banding Association \n| successor = \n| formation = {{Start date|1922}} \n| type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] \n| status = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc --> \n| purpose = Ornithology \n| headquarters  = \n| location = \n| coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template --> \n| region_served = [[Americas]] \n| membership = \n| language = English, Espa\u00f1ol, Portugu\u00eas \n| general = <!-- Secretary General --> \n| leader_title  = <!-- position title for the leader of the org --> \n| leader_name   = <!-- name of leader --> \n| leader_title2 = \n| leader_name2  = \n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3  = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4  = \n| key_people = \n| main_organ  = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc --> \n| parent_organization = <!-- if one --> \n| affiliations  = <!-- if any --> \n| budget = \n| num_staff = \n| num_volunteers = \n| website = {{url|www.afonet.org}} \n| remarks = \n| former name = \n}}\n\nThe '''Association of Field Ornithologists''' (AFO) is an [[Americas|American]] [[ornithology|ornithological]] society, with a strong focus on field studies and [[bird ringing|banding]], priding itself as serving as a bridge between professional and amateur ornithologists.  It was founded in 1922 as the New England Bird Banding Association, then becoming the Northeastern Bird-Banding Association, before expanding its geographical scope and acquiring its current name.  It publishes a twice-yearly newsletter, ''AFO Afield'', as well as the quarterly '''''Journal of Field Ornithology'''''.  The AFO is a member of the [[Ornithological Council]].\n\n==Awards==\n===Skutch Award===\nOfficially named ''The Pamela and Alexander F. Skutch Research Award'', the Skutch Award of up to US$10,000 is presented annually. Applications may be made in English, Spanish or Portuguese by 15 July for the following year.  Preference is given to those who propose field research from a [[Neotropic ecozone|neotropical]] base.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pamela and Alexander F. Skutch Research Award |publisher=Association of Field Ornithologists |url=http://www.afonet.org/grants/Skutch/Skutch.html |accessdate=17 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829055928/http://www.afonet.org/grants/Skutch/Skutch.html |archivedate=29 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe Skutch Award is named for [[Alexander Skutch]].\n\n===Bergstrom Award===\nThe Bergstrom Research Award is presented annually in honor of [[E. Alexander Bergstrom]].\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of ornithology awards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090222223158/http://www.afonet.org/index_english.html Association of Field Ornithologists]\n\n[[Category:Ornithological organizations]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{ornithology-org-stub}}\n{{US-org-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tom Radulovich", "label": "safe", "comment": "ecozone > realm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_of_Field_Ornithologists"}
{"title_page": "The Web Planet", "text_new": "{{short description|1965 Doctor Who serial}}\n{{needsattention|project=Doctor Who|type=muliple|date=June 2017|}}\n{{Lead too short|date=September 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 013\n| serial_name        = The Web Planet\n| show               = DW\n| type               = serial\n| image              = [[File:Captured by the Animus.jpg|250px]]\n| caption            = The Doctor and Vicki are captured in a web by the Animus.\n| doctor             = [[William Hartnell]] ([[First Doctor]])\n| companions         = \n* [[Jacqueline Hill]] ([[Barbara Wright (Doctor Who)|Barbara Wright]])\n* [[William Russell (English actor)|William Russell]] ([[Ian Chesterton]])\n* [[Maureen O'Brien]] ([[Vicki (Doctor Who)|Vicki]])\n| guests             = \n* Catherine Fleming \u2014 Animus voice\n* Roslyn de Winter \u2014 Vrestin\n* Arne Gordon \u2014 Hrostar\n* Arthur Blake \u2014 Hrhoonda\n* Jolyon Booth \u2014 Prapillus\n* Jocelyn Birdsall \u2014 Hlynia\n* [[Martin Jarvis (actor)|Martin Jarvis]] \u2014 Hilio\n* Ian Thompson \u2014 Hetra\n* Barbara Joss \u2014 Nemini\n* [[Robert Jewell]], Jack Pitt, Gerald Taylor, Hugh Lund, [[Kevin Manser]], [[John Scott Martin]] \u2014 The Zarbi\n| director           = [[Richard Martin (British director)|Richard Martin]]\n| writer             = [[Bill Strutton]]\n| script_editor      = [[Dennis Spooner]]\n| producer           = [[Verity Lambert]]\n| executive_producer = None\n| composer           = [[Stock music]] by [[Baschet Brothers|Les Structures Sonores]]\n| production_code    = N<ref>{{cite book |last=Bentham |first=Jeremy |title=Doctor Who: The Early Years |year=1986 |publisher=[[W.H. Allen]] |location=London |isbn=0-491-03612-4 |page=221 |ref=harv }}</ref>\n| series             = [[Doctor Who (season 2)|Season 2]]\n| length             = 6 episodes, 25 minutes each\n| started            = {{Start date|1965|2|13|df=y}}\n| ended              = {{End date|1965|3|20|df=y}}\n| preceding          = ''[[The Romans (Doctor Who)|The Romans]]''\n| following          = ''[[The Crusade (Doctor Who)|The Crusade]]''\n}}\n\n'''''The Web Planet''''' is the fifth serial of the second season of the British [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]'', which was first broadcast in six weekly parts from 13 February 1965 to 20 March 1965. The serial involves the [[Time travel in fiction|time traveller]] the [[First Doctor]] ([[William Hartnell]]) and his travelling [[Companion (Doctor Who)|companions]] [[Ian Chesterton]] ([[William Russell (English actor)|William Russell]]), [[Barbara Wright (Doctor Who)|Barbara Wright]] ([[Jacqueline Hill]]), and [[Vicki (Doctor Who)|Vicki]] ([[Maureen O'Brien]]) allying themselves with the former inhabitants of the planet [[Vortis (Doctor Who)|Vortis]], the Menoptra, as they struggle to win back Vortis from the malignant Animus.\n\n==Plot==\n{{needsattention|project=Doctor Who|type=multiple|date=June 2017|\n{{long plot|date=June 2017|episodes}}\n}}\nAn unknown force pulls the [[TARDIS]] off course and forces it to land on an unidentified planet. Whilst exploring with [[Ian Chesterton|Ian]], the [[First Doctor]] recognises the planet as [[Vortis (Doctor Who)|Vortis]]; however, the presence of several moons in the sky of the normally moonless planet puzzles him.\n\nInside the ship, an unknown force acting through [[Barbara Wright (Doctor Who)|Barbara]]'s gold bracelet draws her outside, leaving [[Vicki (Doctor Who)|Vicki]] alone. The TARDIS is then pulled by an unseen force across the planet's surface.\n\nIn her trance, Barbara walks into a trio of the butterfly-like Menoptra. They remove her bracelet, freeing her of the trance, then debate what to do with her. She escapes, but the Zarbi immediately capture her. Brainwashed through the use of a gold collar, the Zarbi use Barbara to find the Menoptra. The Zarbi take Barbara and the Menoptra called Hrostar to the Crater of Needles, where the Zarbi force them to gather vegetation and drop it into rivers of acid which feed the Animus.\n\nThe Zarbi capture the Doctor and Ian and take them to the Carsinome. There they find Vicki and the TARDIS. They also meet the Animus who forces the Doctor to help it track down the Menoptra invasion force. Ian escapes, whilst the Doctor and Vicki try to bide their time.\n[[File:Menoptra (28807516473).jpg|thumb|left|A Menoptra, on display at the Doctor Who Experience.]]\nIan meets with a Menoptra called Vrestin. He learns that the Menoptra were native to the planet Vortis along with the Zarbi, until a great evil force, the Animus, slowly and gradually took control of the planet through the Zarbi. By the time the Menoptra noticed the danger it was too late, and they had to flee the planet to one of the moons the Animus pulled into orbit around Vortis.\n\nBack in the Carsinome, the Doctor accidentally reveals that the Menoptra spearhead plans to land at a place near the Crater of Needles. The Animus uses this information to ambush them.\n\nThe Zarbi soon locate Ian and Vrestin, but they escape when they fall into a tunnel. Inside they meet the Optera, descendants of the Menoptra who fled the Animus underground. Ian and Vrestin convince the Optera to join them in fighting the Animus.\n\nAt the Crater of Needles, Barbara and Hrostar escape and try to meet up with the spearhead to warn them, but the spearhead is massacred.\n\nAt the Carsinome, the Doctor works out that the Animus uses gold as a conductor to channel its mesmerising force. He counteracts this force to control one of the Zarbi. The Doctor and Vicki escape. They meet up with Barbara and the Menoptra and devise a plan to attack the Carsinome.\n\nThe Doctor and Vicki return to the Carsinome, where the Zarbi take them to the Animus, a great spider-like creature, which mesmerises them. Meanwhile, Barbara and the Menoptra launch their attack on the Carsinome from outside whilst Ian and Vrestin with the Optera reach the Animus from below. They eventually defeat the Animus with a bomb.\n\n==Production==\nThe story had the working title of ''The Webbed Planet''. Episode six was initially titled \"Centre of Terror\". The novelisation restores this title for the sixth chapter.\n\nJacqueline Hill was written out of \"Escape to Danger\" in order to give her a week's holiday and was uncredited on-screen, though she was still credited in ''Radio Times''. She requested that her credit be reinstated when the story was made available for overseas sales, but this was not acted upon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Howe |first1=David J. |authorlink1=David J. Howe |last2=Stammers |first2=Mark |last3=Walker |first3=Stephen James |authorlink3=Stephen James Walker |title=Doctor Who The Handbook \u2013 The First Doctor |year=1994 |publisher=[[Virgin Books|Doctor Who Books]] |location=London |isbn=0-426-20430-1 |page=92 |ref=harv }}</ref>\n\nDaphne Dare created the unique costumes for the varied alien species.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2008-12-20/the-web-planet/|title=The Web Planet \u2605\u2605\u2605|website=Radio Times}}</ref>\n\n===Cast notes===\nNoted [[choreographer]] Roslyn de Winter was hired to create the distinctive movements and stilted speech of the Menoptra. She was so successful that the production team asked her to take on the role of the Menoptra Vrestin (which she accepted). A special credit for de Winter, \"Insect Movement by...\" was included on the closing credits of \"The Zarbi\" to \"The Centre\".\n\nThis serial marked the television debut of Martin Jarvis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/shakespeare/muchadoaboutnothing/martin_jarvis.shtml|title=BBC - Drama - Shakespeare - Much Ado About Nothing - Martin Jarvis as Leonard|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He later appeared as Butler in ''[[Invasion of the Dinosaurs]]'' (1974)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/invasiondinosaurs/detail.shtml|title=BBC - Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide - Invasion of the Dinosaurs - Details|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and as the Governor of Varos in ''[[Vengeance on Varos]]'' (1985).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/vengeancevaros/detail.shtml|title=BBC - Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide - Vengeance on Varos - Details|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast and reception==\n{{Episode table\n |background =\n |series = 6 |title = 20 | aux1=6 | airdate = 10 | viewers = 6 | aux4 = 16 | country = UK\n |seriesT    = Episode\n |aux1T      = Run time\n |aux4T      = Archive\n |aux4R      = <ref name=\"ArchiveStatus\" />\n |viewersR   = <ref name=\"AllRatings\" />\n |episodes   = \n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 1\n |Title              = The Web Planet\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|2|13|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 13.5\n |Aux1               = 23:57\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 2\n |Title              = The Zarbi\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|2|20|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 12.5\n |Aux1               = 23:20\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 3\n |Title              = Escape to Danger\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|2|27|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 12.5\n |Aux1               = 22:52\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 4\n |Title              = Crater of Needles\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|3|6|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 13.0\n |Aux1               = 25:50\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 5\n |Title              = Invasion\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|3|13|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 12.0\n |Aux1               = 26:04\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 6\n |Title              = The Centre\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|3|20|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 11.5\n |Aux1               = 24:28\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n}}\nThe first episode of the serial was watched by 13.5 million viewers, the highest number for any ''Doctor Who'' episode in the 1960s.\n\nThe serial was believed lost in the [[Doctor Who missing episodes|BBC's early 1970s purge]] until negative film prints of all six episodes were recovered from BBC Enterprises in the late 1970s. Unedited prints of all six episodes were also discovered in [[Nigeria]] in 1984. The BBC holds two different versions of episode six; one in which the \"Next Episode\" caption referred to \"The Lion\" and the other with the caption naming \"[[The Space Museum]]\", which was the only story still available for sale by the BBC in 1974. (The different caption is ''not'' due to ''[[The Crusade (Doctor Who)|The Crusade]]'' being withheld from sale to Arab countries as is commonly thought, since the package of serials sold to Arabic countries did not extend beyond ''[[The Rescue (Doctor Who)|The Rescue]]''.)<ref>{{cite book |last=Molesworth |first=Richard |title=Wiped! Doctor Who's Missing Episodes |pages=316, 419 |publisher=Telos Publishing Ltd |year=2010 |ISBN=978-1-84583-037-3 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Mark Braxton of ''[[Radio Times]]'' acknowledged the effort put into the costumes and \"superbly atmospheric\" sets, despite the fact they did not hold up well. He felt that the story had an \"almost total absence of excitement\" and might not even work as a four-parter, but it did have ambition and a deeper meaning about good versus evil.<ref name=\"Radio Times\">{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Braxton|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2008-12-21/the-web-planet|title=Doctor Who: The Web Planet|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=21 December 2008|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> Neela Debnath of ''[[The Independent]]'' stated that ''The Web Planet'' was \"enjoyable\" with ambitious writing that \"lacks impact given the poor quality of the visuals\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Neela|last=Debnath|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/02/28/review-of-doctor-who-the-web-planet-series-2/|title=Review of Doctor Who \u2018The Web Planet\u2019 (Series 2)|work=[[The Independent]]|date=28 February 2012|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref> Den of Geek named ''The Web Planet'' as one of the ten most underrated classic ''Doctor Who'' serials, noting that it \"is a joy for being so ''different''\" even if \"the ambition might outstrip the execution\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/doctor-who/20089/ten-under-rated-classic-doctor-who-stories|title=Ten Under-rated Classic Doctor Who Stories|publisher=Den of Geek|date=6 July 2009|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>  Paul Cornell, Martin Day and Keith Topping said the story was \"Imaginative, ambitious, and, by modern standards, slow and silly looking. It's hard to judge a story that, at the time, was astonishing but has aged so badly.\"  They nevertheless said \"You've got to appreciate lofty ambitions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/webplanet/detail.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide \u2013 The Web Planet \u2013 Details|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial Releases==\n===In print===\n{{Infobox book\n|name = Doctor Who and the Zarbi\n|image = Doctor Who and the Zarbi.jpg\n|border = yes\n|caption = Cover of thre Target Books reprint\n|author = [[Bill Strutton]]\n|cover_artist = John Woods <small>(original publication)</small> <br />[[Chris Achilleos]] <small>(Target reprint)</small>\n|publisher = Frederick Muller Ltd <small>(original publication)</small><br />[[Target Books]]<small>(reprint)</small>\n|series = [[List of Doctor Who novelisations|''Doctor Who'' novelisations]]\n|release_number = 73\n|release_date = 16 September 1965<small>(original publication)</small>  <br />2 May 1973 <small>(Target reprint)</small>\n|pages = \n|isbn= 0-426-10129-4\n}}\nThe serial was the second to be novelised by the publisher [[Frederick Muller]]. It was written by [[Bill Strutton]] under the title ''Doctor Who and the Zarbi'' in 16 September 1965. In 1973 [[Target Books]] acquired the rights to the novelisation and reprinted it as one of the first in their long-running series of ''Doctor Who'' novelisations, although when the imprint began numbering the books in the series, ''The Zarbi'' was listed as Number 73 in the series. A [[Dutch language|Dutch]] translation was published in the [[Netherlands]] in 1974, and a [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] one in 1983.\n\nIn 2005 the novel was also issued by BBC Audio as part of the ''Doctor Who: Travels in Time and Space'' [[Doctor Who audio releases|audio book]] collectors' tin, read by William Russell.\n\n===Home media===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:The Web Planet UK DVD Cover.jpg|thumb|left|UK DVD front cover]] -->\n''The Web Planet'' was released on a double [[VHS]] in 1990. In [[North America]] it was released as a single VHS. It was released on [[DVD]] on 3 October 2005 in the United Kingdom (Region 2), 3 November 2005 in Region 4, and 5 September 2006 in Region 1.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"ArchiveStatus\">{{Cite web|url= http://gallifreyone.com/episode.php?id=n|title= The Web Planet|publisher = Outpost Gallifrey|author = Shaun Lyon|date = 2007-03-31|accessdate = 2008-08-30|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080618190304/http://www.gallifreyone.com/episode.php?id=n <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 18 June 2008|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"AllRatings\">{{cite web|title=Ratings Guide |url=http://guide.doctorwhonews.net/info.php?detail=ratings&type=date |website=Doctor Who News |accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|First Doctor}}\n*{{BBCCDW | id=webplanet | title=The Web Planet}}\n*[http://dwasonline.barryrward.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=34&limit=1&limitstart=0 Doctor Who Appreciation Society interview with Verity Lambert about producing ''The Web Planet'']\n\n===Reviews===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070806052109/http://www.gallifreyone.com/review.php?id=n ''The Web Planet''] reviews at [[Outpost Gallifrey]]\n\n===Target novelisation===\n*{{Isfdb title|id=10649|title=Doctor Who and the Zarbi}}\n\n{{Doctor Who episodes|C2}}\n{{First Doctor stories}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Web Planet, The}}\n[[Category:First Doctor serials]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who serials novelised by Bill Strutton]]\n[[Category:1965 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Fiction about insects]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1965 Doctor Who serial}}\n{{needsattention|project=Doctor Who|type=muliple|date=June 2017|}}\n{{Lead too short|date=September 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 013\n| serial_name        = The Web Planet\n| show               = DW\n| type               = serial\n| image              = [[File:Captured by the Animus.jpg|250px]]\n| caption            = The Doctor and Vicki are captured in a web by the Animus.\n| doctor             = [[William Hartnell]] ([[First Doctor]])\n| companions         = \n* [[Jacqueline Hill]] ([[Barbara Wright (Doctor Who)|Barbara Wright]])\n* [[William Russell (English actor)|William Russell]] ([[Ian Chesterton]])\n* [[Maureen O'Brien]] ([[Vicki (Doctor Who)|Vicki]])\n| guests             = \n* Catherine Fleming \u2014 Animus voice\n* Roslyn de Winter \u2014 Vrestin\n* Arne Gordon \u2014 Hrostar\n* Arthur Blake \u2014 Hrhoonda\n* Jolyon Booth \u2014 Prapillus\n* Jocelyn Birdsall \u2014 Hlynia\n* [[Martin Jarvis (actor)|Martin Jarvis]] \u2014 Hilio\n* Ian Thompson \u2014 Hetra\n* Barbara Joss \u2014 Nemini\n* [[Robert Jewell]], Jack Pitt, Gerald Taylor, Hugh Lund, [[Kevin Manser]], [[John Scott Martin]] \u2014 The Zarbi\n| director           = [[Richard Martin (British director)|Richard Martin]]\n| writer             = [[Bill Strutton]]\n| script_editor      = [[Dennis Spooner]]\n| producer           = [[Verity Lambert]]\n| executive_producer = None\n| composer           = [[Stock music]] by [[Baschet Brothers|Les Structures Sonores]]\n| production_code    = N<ref>{{cite book |last=Bentham |first=Jeremy |title=Doctor Who: The Early Years |year=1986 |publisher=[[W.H. Allen]] |location=London |isbn=0-491-03612-4 |page=221 |ref=harv }}</ref>\n| series             = [[Doctor Who (season 2)|Season 2]]\n| length             = 6 episodes, 25 minutes each\n| started            = {{Start date|1965|2|13|df=y}}\n| ended              = {{End date|1965|3|20|df=y}}\n| preceding          = ''[[The Romans (Doctor Who)|The Romans]]''\n| following          = ''[[The Crusade (Doctor Who)|The Crusade]]''\n}}\n\n'''''The Web Planet''''' is the fifth serial of the second season of the British [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]'', which was first broadcast in six weekly parts from 13 February 1965 to 20 March 1965. The serial involves the [[Time travel in fiction|time traveller]] the [[First Doctor]] ([[William Hartnell]]) and his travelling [[Companion (Doctor Who)|companions]] [[Ian Chesterton]] ([[William Russell (English actor)|William Russell]]), [[Barbara Wright (Doctor Who)|Barbara Wright]] ([[Jacqueline Hill]]), and [[Vicki (Doctor Who)|Vicki]] ([[Maureen O'Brien]]) allying themselves with the former inhabitants of the planet [[Vortis (Doctor Who)|Vortis]], the Menoptra, as they struggle to win back Vortis from the malignant Animus.\n\n==Plot==\n{{needsattention|project=Doctor Who|type=multiple|date=June 2017|\n{{long plot|date=June 2017|episodes}}\n}}\nAn unknown force pulls the [[TARDIS]] off course and forces it to land on an unknown planet. Whilst exploring with [[Ian Chesterton|Ian]], the [[First Doctor]] recognises the planet as [[Vortis (Doctor Who)|Vortis]]; however, the presence of several moons in the sky of the normally moonless planet puzzles him.\n\nInside the ship, an unknown force acting through [[Barbara Wright (Doctor Who)|Barbara]]'s gold bracelet draws her outside, leaving [[Vicki (Doctor Who)|Vicki]] alone. The TARDIS is then pulled by an unseen force across the planet's surface.\n\nIn her trance, Barbara walks into a trio of the butterfly-like Menoptra. They remove her bracelet, freeing her of the trance, then debate what to do with her. She escapes, but the Zarbi immediately capture her. Brainwashed through the use of a gold collar, the Zarbi use Barbara to find the Menoptra. The Zarbi take Barbara and the Menoptra called Hrostar to the Crater of Needles, where the Zarbi force them to gather vegetation and drop it into rivers of acid which feed the Animus.\n\nThe Zarbi capture the Doctor and Ian and take them to the Carsinome. There they find Vicki and the TARDIS. They also meet the Animus who forces the Doctor to help it track down the Menoptra invasion force. Ian escapes, whilst the Doctor and Vicki try to bide their time.\n[[File:Menoptra (28807516473).jpg|thumb|left|A Menoptra, on display at the Doctor Who Experience.]]\nIan meets with a Menoptra called Vrestin. He learns that the Menoptra were native to the planet Vortis along with the Zarbi, until a great evil force, the Animus, slowly and gradually took control of the planet through the Zarbi. By the time the Menoptra noticed the danger it was too late, and they had to flee the planet to one of the moons the Animus pulled into orbit around Vortis.\n\nBack in the Carsinome, the Doctor accidentally reveals that the Menoptra spearhead plans to land at a place near the Crater of Needles. The Animus uses this information to ambush them.\n\nThe Zarbi soon locate Ian and Vrestin, but they escape when they fall into a tunnel. Inside they meet the Optera, descendants of the Menoptra who fled the Animus underground. Ian and Vrestin convince the Optera to join them in fighting the Animus.\n\nAt the Crater of Needles, Barbara and Hrostar escape and try to meet up with the spearhead to warn them, but the spearhead is massacred.\n\nAt the Carsinome, the Doctor works out that the Animus uses gold as a conductor to channel its mesmerising force. He counteracts this force to control one of the Zarbi. The Doctor and Vicki escape. They meet up with Barbara and the Menoptra and devise a plan to attack the Carsinome.\n\nThe Doctor and Vicki return to the Carsinome, where the Zarbi take them to the Animus, a great spider-like creature, which mesmerises them. Meanwhile, Barbara and the Menoptra launch their attack on the Carsinome from outside whilst Ian and Vrestin with the Optera reach the Animus from below. They eventually defeat the Animus with a bomb.\n\n==Production==\nThe story had the working title of ''The Webbed Planet''. Episode six was initially titled \"Centre of Terror\". The novelisation restores this title for the sixth chapter.\n\nJacqueline Hill was written out of \"Escape to Danger\" in order to give her a week's holiday and was uncredited on-screen, though she was still credited in ''Radio Times''. She requested that her credit be reinstated when the story was made available for overseas sales, but this was not acted upon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Howe |first1=David J. |authorlink1=David J. Howe |last2=Stammers |first2=Mark |last3=Walker |first3=Stephen James |authorlink3=Stephen James Walker |title=Doctor Who The Handbook \u2013 The First Doctor |year=1994 |publisher=[[Virgin Books|Doctor Who Books]] |location=London |isbn=0-426-20430-1 |page=92 |ref=harv }}</ref>\n\nDaphne Dare created the unique costumes for the varied alien species.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2008-12-20/the-web-planet/|title=The Web Planet \u2605\u2605\u2605|website=Radio Times}}</ref>\n\n===Cast notes===\nNoted [[choreographer]] Roslyn de Winter was hired to create the distinctive movements and stilted speech of the Menoptra. She was so successful that the production team asked her to take on the role of the Menoptra Vrestin (which she accepted). A special credit for de Winter, \"Insect Movement by...\" was included on the closing credits of \"The Zarbi\" to \"The Centre\".\n\nThis serial marked the television debut of Martin Jarvis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/shakespeare/muchadoaboutnothing/martin_jarvis.shtml|title=BBC - Drama - Shakespeare - Much Ado About Nothing - Martin Jarvis as Leonard|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He later appeared as Butler in ''[[Invasion of the Dinosaurs]]'' (1974)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/invasiondinosaurs/detail.shtml|title=BBC - Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide - Invasion of the Dinosaurs - Details|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and as the Governor of Varos in ''[[Vengeance on Varos]]'' (1985).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/vengeancevaros/detail.shtml|title=BBC - Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide - Vengeance on Varos - Details|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast and reception==\n{{Episode table\n |background =\n |series = 6 |title = 20 | aux1=6 | airdate = 10 | viewers = 6 | aux4 = 16 | country = UK\n |seriesT    = Episode\n |aux1T      = Run time\n |aux4T      = Archive\n |aux4R      = <ref name=\"ArchiveStatus\" />\n |viewersR   = <ref name=\"AllRatings\" />\n |episodes   = \n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 1\n |Title              = The Web Planet\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|2|13|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 13.5\n |Aux1               = 23:57\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 2\n |Title              = The Zarbi\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|2|20|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 12.5\n |Aux1               = 23:20\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 3\n |Title              = Escape to Danger\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|2|27|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 12.5\n |Aux1               = 22:52\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 4\n |Title              = Crater of Needles\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|3|6|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 13.0\n |Aux1               = 25:50\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 5\n |Title              = Invasion\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|3|13|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 12.0\n |Aux1               = 26:04\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Web Planet\n |EpisodeNumber      = 6\n |Title              = The Centre\n |RTitle             = \n |OriginalAirDate    = {{Start date|1965|3|20|df=y}}\n |Viewers            = 11.5\n |Aux1               = 24:28\n |Aux4               = 16mm t/r\n |LineColor          = \n}}\n}}\nThe first episode of the serial was watched by 13.5 million viewers, the highest number for any ''Doctor Who'' episode in the 1960s.\n\nThe serial was believed lost in the [[Doctor Who missing episodes|BBC's early 1970s purge]] until negative film prints of all six episodes were recovered from BBC Enterprises in the late 1970s. Unedited prints of all six episodes were also discovered in [[Nigeria]] in 1984. The BBC holds two different versions of episode six; one in which the \"Next Episode\" caption referred to \"The Lion\" and the other with the caption naming \"[[The Space Museum]]\", which was the only story still available for sale by the BBC in 1974. (The different caption is ''not'' due to ''[[The Crusade (Doctor Who)|The Crusade]]'' being withheld from sale to Arab countries as is commonly thought, since the package of serials sold to Arabic countries did not extend beyond ''[[The Rescue (Doctor Who)|The Rescue]]''.)<ref>{{cite book |last=Molesworth |first=Richard |title=Wiped! Doctor Who's Missing Episodes |pages=316, 419 |publisher=Telos Publishing Ltd |year=2010 |ISBN=978-1-84583-037-3 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Mark Braxton of ''[[Radio Times]]'' acknowledged the effort put into the costumes and \"superbly atmospheric\" sets, despite the fact they did not hold up well. He felt that the story had an \"almost total absence of excitement\" and might not even work as a four-parter, but it did have ambition and a deeper meaning about good versus evil.<ref name=\"Radio Times\">{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Braxton|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2008-12-21/the-web-planet|title=Doctor Who: The Web Planet|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=21 December 2008|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> Neela Debnath of ''[[The Independent]]'' stated that ''The Web Planet'' was \"enjoyable\" with ambitious writing that \"lacks impact given the poor quality of the visuals\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Neela|last=Debnath|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/02/28/review-of-doctor-who-the-web-planet-series-2/|title=Review of Doctor Who \u2018The Web Planet\u2019 (Series 2)|work=[[The Independent]]|date=28 February 2012|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref> Den of Geek named ''The Web Planet'' as one of the ten most underrated classic ''Doctor Who'' serials, noting that it \"is a joy for being so ''different''\" even if \"the ambition might outstrip the execution\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/doctor-who/20089/ten-under-rated-classic-doctor-who-stories|title=Ten Under-rated Classic Doctor Who Stories|publisher=Den of Geek|date=6 July 2009|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>  Paul Cornell, Martin Day and Keith Topping said the story was \"Imaginative, ambitious, and, by modern standards, slow and silly looking. It's hard to judge a story that, at the time, was astonishing but has aged so badly.\"  They nevertheless said \"You've got to appreciate lofty ambitions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/webplanet/detail.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide \u2013 The Web Planet \u2013 Details|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial Releases==\n===In print===\n{{Infobox book\n|name = Doctor Who and the Zarbi\n|image = Doctor Who and the Zarbi.jpg\n|border = yes\n|caption = Cover of thre Target Books reprint\n|author = [[Bill Strutton]]\n|cover_artist = John Woods <small>(original publication)</small> <br />[[Chris Achilleos]] <small>(Target reprint)</small>\n|publisher = Frederick Muller Ltd <small>(original publication)</small><br />[[Target Books]]<small>(reprint)</small>\n|series = [[List of Doctor Who novelisations|''Doctor Who'' novelisations]]\n|release_number = 73\n|release_date = 16 September 1965<small>(original publication)</small>  <br />2 May 1973 <small>(Target reprint)</small>\n|pages = \n|isbn= 0-426-10129-4\n}}\nThe serial was the second to be novelised by the publisher [[Frederick Muller]]. It was written by [[Bill Strutton]] under the title ''Doctor Who and the Zarbi'' in 16 September 1965. In 1973 [[Target Books]] acquired the rights to the novelisation and reprinted it as one of the first in their long-running series of ''Doctor Who'' novelisations, although when the imprint began numbering the books in the series, ''The Zarbi'' was listed as Number 73 in the series. A [[Dutch language|Dutch]] translation was published in the [[Netherlands]] in 1974, and a [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] one in 1983.\n\nIn 2005 the novel was also issued by BBC Audio as part of the ''Doctor Who: Travels in Time and Space'' [[Doctor Who audio releases|audio book]] collectors' tin, read by William Russell.\n\n===Home media===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:The Web Planet UK DVD Cover.jpg|thumb|left|UK DVD front cover]] -->\n''The Web Planet'' was released on a double [[VHS]] in 1990. In [[North America]] it was released as a single VHS. It was released on [[DVD]] on 3 October 2005 in the United Kingdom (Region 2), 3 November 2005 in Region 4, and 5 September 2006 in Region 1.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"ArchiveStatus\">{{Cite web|url= http://gallifreyone.com/episode.php?id=n|title= The Web Planet|publisher = Outpost Gallifrey|author = Shaun Lyon|date = 2007-03-31|accessdate = 2008-08-30|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080618190304/http://www.gallifreyone.com/episode.php?id=n <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 18 June 2008|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"AllRatings\">{{cite web|title=Ratings Guide |url=http://guide.doctorwhonews.net/info.php?detail=ratings&type=date |website=Doctor Who News |accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|First Doctor}}\n*{{BBCCDW | id=webplanet | title=The Web Planet}}\n*[http://dwasonline.barryrward.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=34&limit=1&limitstart=0 Doctor Who Appreciation Society interview with Verity Lambert about producing ''The Web Planet'']\n\n===Reviews===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070806052109/http://www.gallifreyone.com/review.php?id=n ''The Web Planet''] reviews at [[Outpost Gallifrey]]\n\n===Target novelisation===\n*{{Isfdb title|id=10649|title=Doctor Who and the Zarbi}}\n\n{{Doctor Who episodes|C2}}\n{{First Doctor stories}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Web Planet, The}}\n[[Category:First Doctor serials]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who serials novelised by Bill Strutton]]\n[[Category:1965 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Fiction about insects]]\